Loughborough University]]<br />[[Manchester]] ([[Broughton Park RUFC]], The Hough End Centre, [[Manchester Aquatics Centre]])<br />[[Celtic Manor Resort]] & [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] ([[Newport High School, Bettws Lane|Newport High School]]/Active Living Centre, The Celtic Academy)\n|-\n|Knock-out phase\n|[[The Vale Resort]]<br />[[Hazelwood (rugby ground)|London Irish RFC]]<br />[[Surrey Sports Park]]<br />[[Swansea University]]<br />[[Pennyhill Park Hotel]]<br />[[Sport Wales National Centre]]<br />[[Celtic Manor Resort]] & [[Newport, Wales|Newport]]<br />The Lensbury & [[St Mary's University, Twickenham|St Mary's University]]\n|}\n\n==Qualifying==\n{{Main article|2015 Rugby World Cup qualifying}}\nOf the 20 teams competing at the 2015 World Cup, 12 of them qualified by finishing in the top three places in their pools in the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]]. The other eight teams qualified through regional competition. As the host nation, England qualified automatically. The qualification process for the remaining teams incorporated existing regional competitions such as the [[European Nations Cup (rugby union)|European Nations Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Major changes made to RWC qualifying |url=http://www.worldcupweb.com/rugby/news/viewarticle.asp?id=3873 |publisher=worldcupweb.com |date=10 May 2007 |accessdate=30 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Qualified teams===\nTwenty teams played in the final tournament. They are listed below, along with their pre-tournament positions in the [[World Rugby Rankings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldrugby.org/rankings|title=World Rugby|work=worldrugby.org}}</ref> The list of teams was the same as in the 2003 tournament.\n\n{{col begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n;[[Asia Rugby]] <small>(1)</small>\n* {{ru|JPN}} <small>(13)</small>\n;[[Rugby Africa]] <small>(2)</small>\n* {{ru|RSA}} <small>(3)</small>\n* {{ru|NAM}} <small>(20)</small>\n;[[Sudam\u00e9rica Rugby]] <small>(2)</small>\n* {{ru|ARG}} <small>(8)</small>\n* {{ru|URU}} <small>(19)</small>\n;[[North America Caribbean Rugby Association|NACRA]] <small>(2)</small>\n* {{ru|CAN}} <small>(18)</small>\n* {{ru|USA}} <small>(15)</small>\n{{col-4}}\n;[[Rugby Europe]] <small>(8)</small>\n* {{ru|ENG}} <small>(4)</small>\n* {{ru|FRA}} <small>(7)</small>\n* {{ru|GEO}} <small>(16)</small>\n* {{ru|IRE}} <small>(6)</small>\n* {{ru|ITA}} <small>(14)</small>\n* {{ru|ROU}} <small>(17)</small>\n* {{ru|SCO}} <small>(10)</small>\n* {{ru|WAL}} <small>(5)</small>\n{{col-4}}\n;[[Oceania Rugby]] <small>(5)</small>\n* {{ru|AUS}} <small>(2)</small>\n* {{ru|FIJ}} <small>(9)</small>\n* {{ru|NZL}} <small>(1)</small>\n* {{ru|SAM}} <small>(12)</small>\n* {{ru|TGA}} <small>(11)</small>\n{{col-4}}\n<!-- This map should not be removed as it is shows the status of qualification by failed or not enter-->\n[[File:Rugby World Cup 2015.svg|thumb|400px|{{legend|#2020d0|Country qualified for World Cup}} {{legend|#f0c020|Country did not qualify}} {{legend|#ababab|Country not an IRB member}}]]\n{{col end}}\n\n==Draw==\nSeedings for the pools of the 2015 World Cup were based on the teams' respective [[World Rugby|IRB]] [[World Rugby Rankings|Rankings]]. The draw, hosted by [[Will Greenwood]], was conducted on 3 December 2012 in London, and used the World Rankings as of that day, just after the [[2012 end-of-year rugby union internationals]], which finished on 1 December 2012.<ref name=rankings>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldrugby.org/rankings |title=IRB World Rankings at 3 December 2012 |publisher=World Rugby |date=3 December 2012 |accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> The 12 automatic qualifiers from 2011 were allocated to their respective bands based on their rankings:\n\n* '''Band 1''', made up of the top 4 automatic qualifiers, (1\u20134)\n* '''Band 2''', made up of the next 4 automatic qualifiers, (5\u20138)\n* '''Band 3''', made up of the next 4 automatic qualifiers (9\u201312)\n\nThe remaining 8 qualifying places were allocated to Bands 4 and 5, based on previous World Cup playing strength;\n\n* '''Band 4''', made up of Oceania 1, Europe 1, Asia 1 and Americas 1\n* '''Band 5''', made up of Africa 1, Europe 2, Americas 2 and play-off winner\n\nThis meant the 20 teams, qualified and qualifiers, were seeded thus:\n\n{|\n|- style=\"text-align:left\"\n! style=\"width:10em\"|Pot 1\n! style=\"width:10em\"|Pot 2\n! style=\"width:10em\"|Pot 3\n! style=\"width:12em\"|Pot 4\n! style=\"width:14em\"|Pot 5\n|- class=\"plainlist wraplinks\" style=\"vertical-align:top\"\n|\n*{{ru|NZL|name=New Zealand}} <small>(1)</small>\n*{{ru|RSA|name=South Africa}} <small>(2)</small>\n*{{ru|AUS}} <small>(3)</small>\n*{{ru|FRA}} <small>(4)</small>\n|\n*{{ru|ENG}} <small>(5)</small>\n*{{ru|IRE}} <small>(6)</small>\n*{{ru|SAM}} <small>(7)</small>\n*{{ru|ARG}} <small>(8)</small>\n|\n*{{ru|WAL}} <small>(9)</small>\n*{{ru|ITA}} <small>(10)</small>\n*{{ru|TON}} <small>(11)</small>\n*{{ru|SCO}} <small>(12)</small>\n|\n*{{ru|CAN}} <small>(Americas 1)</small>\n*{{ru|JPN}} <small>(Asia 1)</small>\n*{{ru|GEO}} <small>(Europe 1)</small>\n*{{ru|FIJ}} {{wbr}}<small>{{nowrap|(Oceania 1)}}</small>\n|\n*{{ru|NAM}} <small>(Africa 1)</small>\n*{{ru|USA|name=United {{wbr}}States}} <small>{{nowrap|(Americas 2)}}</small>\n*{{ru|ROM}} <small>(Europe 2)</small>\n*{{ru|URU}} <small>(Repechage)</small>\n|}\n\nThe draw saw a representative randomly draw a ball from a pot, the first drawn ball goes to Pool A, the second Pool B, the third Pool C and the fourth Pool D. The draw began with Pot 5, drawn by All Blacks captain [[Richie McCaw]], followed by Pot 4, drawn by RWC 2015 Ambassador and English women's international [[Maggie Alphonsi]], then Pot 3, drawn by [[Mayor of London]] [[Boris Johnson]], Pot 2, drawn by the then Chief Executive for RWC 2015 [[Debbie Jevans]], and finally Pot 1, drawn by IRB chairman [[Bernard Lapasset]].\n\n===Draw criticism===\nThe timing of the draw drew criticism due to the long period between the draw occurring and the commencement of the tournament - three years.<ref name=\"Fox Sports\">{{cite web|title=Rugby World Cup Scout: draw changes, Hawk-Eye, concussion|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/rugby/rugby-world-cup-scout-draw-changes-hawk-eye-concussion/story-e6frf4pu-1227489881779|website=Fox Sports|publisher=Fox Sports Australia|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref> Indeed, by the time of the pool match between England and Wales on 26 September, pool A contained the 2nd, 3rd and 4th (Australia, England and Wales) ranked teams in the world.<ref name=\"World Rugby Archives\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldrugby.org/rankings|title=World Rugby|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> Following England's elimination at the pool stage after defeats by Australia and Wales, Wales coach [[Warren Gatland]] noted that \"Everyone is making a thing about the first home country to hold a World Cup to miss out on the quarter-finals, but the stupid thing, as we all know, is why was the World Cup draw done three years ago? That's just ridiculous as far as I am concerned. If they had followed the football model, then we wouldn't be in this position. There are other people outside this who need to have a look at themselves and why those decisions were made, and you have got to feel sorry for the people involved and who this has affected\".<ref name=\"Garland quote\">{{cite web|title=Gatland condemns 'ridiculous' World Cup draw|url=http://www.itv.com/rugbyworldcup/gatland-condemns-ridiculous-world-cup-draw|website=itv|publisher=itv|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref> The chief executive of World Rugby [[Brett Gosper]] subsequently acknowledged criticisms, saying \"We\u2019ll look at that next time to see if it\u2019s possible to make the draw closer to the tournament\".<ref name=\"Guardian quote\">{{cite web|last1=Kitson|first1=Robert|title=Rugby World Cup: draw for 2019 set to take place closer to tournament|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/aug/18/rugby-world-cup-2019-draw|website=guardian.co,uk|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Squads==\n{{Main article|2015 Rugby World Cup squads}}\n\nEach country was allowed a squad of 31 players for the tournament. These squads were to be submitted to World Rugby by a deadline of 31 August 2015. Once the squad was submitted, a player could be replaced if injured, but would not be allowed to return to the squad. There was also a stand-down period of 48 hours before the new player was allowed to take the field. Hence, a replacement player called into a squad on the eve of a game would not be permitted to play in that game.<ref>{{cite news |title=The strict 48 hour rule Warren Gatland must abide by if Wales face a World Cup hooking crisis |work=Wales Online |first=Anthony |last=Woolford |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-news/strict-48-hour-rule-warren-9968431 |publisher=Media Wales |date=1 September 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011144746/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-news/strict-48-hour-rule-warren-9968431 |archivedate=11 October 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Pool stage==\nThe first round, or pool stage, saw the 20 teams divided into four pools of five teams, using the same format that was used in [[2003 Rugby World Cup|2003]], [[2007 Rugby World Cup|2007]], and [[2011 Rugby World Cup|2011]]. Each pool was a [[round-robin tournament|single round-robin]] of ten games, in which each team played one match against each of the other teams in the same pool. Teams were awarded four points for a win, two points for a draw and none for a defeat. A team scoring four [[Try (rugby)|tries]] in one match scored a bonus point, as did a team that lost by fewer than eight points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rugbyworldcup.com/tournament-rules|title=Tournament rules|work=rugbyworldcup.com|access-date=27 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928072157/https://www.rugbyworldcup.com/tournament-rules|archive-date=28 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:98%\"\n|-\n!width=25%|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A|Pool A]]\n!width=25%|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool B|Pool B]]\n!width=25%|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool C|Pool C]]\n!width=25%|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool D|Pool D]]\n|-\n|\n{{ru|AUS}}<br />\n{{ru|ENG}}<br />\n{{ru|WAL}}<br />\n{{ru|FIJ}}<br />\n{{ru|URU}}\n|\n{{ru|RSA}}<br />\n{{ru|SAM}}<br />\n{{ru|SCO}}<br />\n{{ru|JPN}}<br />\n{{ru|USA}}\n|\n{{ru|NZL}}<br />\n{{ru|ARG}}<br />\n{{ru|TON}}<br />\n{{ru|GEO}}<br />\n{{ru|NAM}}\n|\n{{ru|FRA}}<br />\n{{ru|IRE}}<br />\n{{ru|ITA}}<br />\n{{ru|CAN}}<br />\n{{ru|ROM}}\n|}\n\nThe teams finishing in the top two of each pool would advance to the quarter-finals. The top three teams of each pool received automatic qualification to the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]] (Japan had already automatically qualified as hosts).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/rugby-union/32430465|title=Rugby World Cup 2015: fixtures, results and standings|date=|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\t\n\n;Tie-breaking criteria\nIf two or more teams were tied on match points, the following tiebreakers would apply:<ref name=\"2015 Rugby World Cup - Tournament Rules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/tournament-rules |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201205525/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/tournament-rules |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 December 2014 |title=Rugby World Cup 2015 Tournament Rules \u2013 Article 1.1.3 |date=September 2015 |publisher=World Rugby |accessdate=1 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\n# The winner of the match between the two teams;\n# Difference between points scored for and points scored against in all pool matches;\n# Difference between tries scored for and tries scored against in all pool matches;\n# Points scored in all pool matches;\n# Most tries scored in all pool matches;\n# Official [[World Rugby Rankings]] as of 12 October 2015.\n\nIf three teams were tied on points, the above criteria would be used to decide first place in the Pool, and then the criteria would be used again (starting from criteria 1) to decide second place in the Pool.\n\n{{2015 Rugby World Cup Quarter Final Qualifiers}}\n\n<small>'''Pld''' = Number of games played; '''W''' = Number of games won; '''D''' = Number of games drawn; '''L''' = Number of games lost; '''TF''' = Number of tries scored (tries for); '''PF''' = Number of points scored in the game (points for); '''PA''' = Number of points scored against the team (points against); '''+/\u2013''' = Points difference, PF\u2013PA; '''BP''' = Bonus (pool) points; '''Pts''' = Total number of (pool) points.</small>\n\n===Pool A===\n[[File:England vs Australia 2015 RWC (2).jpg|thumb|Australia beat England 33\u201313 at Twickenham Stadium in London.]]\n{{Main article|2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A}}\n{{2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=15%|\n!width=25%|\n!width=10%|\n!width=25%|\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|18 September 2015||align=right|{{ru-rt|ENG}}||align=center|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A#England vs Fiji|35\u201311]]||{{ru|FIJ}}||[[Twickenham Stadium]], [[London]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|20 September 2015||align=right|{{ru-rt|WAL}}||align=center|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A#Wales vs Uruguay|54\u20139]]||{{ru|URU}}||[[Millennium Stadium]], [[Cardiff]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|23 September 2015||align=right|{{ru-rt|AUS}}||align=center|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A#Australia vs Fiji|28\u201313]]||{{ru|FIJ}}||[[Millennium Stadium]], [[Cardiff]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|26 September 2015||align=right|{{ru-rt|ENG}}||align=center|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A#England vs Wales|25\u201328]]||{{ru|WAL}}||[[Twickenham Stadium]], [[London]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|27 September 2015||align=right|{{ru-rt|AUS}}||align=center|[[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A#Australia vs Uruguay|65\u20133]]||{{ru|URU}}||[[Villa Park]], [[Birmingham]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|1 October 2015