] rated the game 1.5/10, calling it \"unbearable to play\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/09/04/rugby-world-cup-2015-review|title=Rugby World Cup 2015 Review|first=Nathan|last=Lawrence|date=4 September 2015|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905091810/http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/09/04/rugby%2Dworld%2Dcup%2D2015%2Dreview|archive-date=5 September 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Tickets==\nTicket prices were announced in November 2013 with general sale applications launching in September 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=2.3m tickets for Rugby World Cup 2015 |url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/home/news/newsid=2069664.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203034714/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/home/news/newsid%3D2069664.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 December 2013 |work=rugbyworldcup.com |publisher=International Rugby Board |date=27 November 2013 |accessdate=27 November 2013 }}</ref> Adult ticket prices started at \u00a315 for pool matches and children's tickets were available from \u00a37 at 41 of the 48 matches. Tickets for the World Cup final ranged from \u00a3150 to \u00a3715.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rugby World Cup 2015: Cheapest Twickenham final ticket is \u00a3150|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/25121033|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=27 November 2013|accessdate=27 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2015 Rugby World Cup warm-up matches]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|2015 Rugby World Cup}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151103061515/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/ 2015 RWC official website] (Archived)\n*[http://www.worldrugby.org/ World Rugby] \u2013 official site\n\n{{2015 Rugby World Cup}}\n{{2015 Rugby World Cup venues}}\n{{2015 Rugby World Cup referees}}\n{{Rugby Union World Cup}}\n{{World championships in 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Cup}}\n[[Category:2015 Rugby World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:Rugby World Cup tournaments|2015]]\n[[Category:2015\u201316 in English rugby union]]\n[[Category:2015\u201316 in Welsh rugby union]]\n[[Category:2015 rugby union tournaments for national teams]]\n[[Category:International rugby union competitions hosted by Wales]]\n[[Category:International rugby union competitions hosted by England]]\n[[Category:September 2015 sports events in the United Kingdom|Rugby World Cup 2015]]\n[[Category:October 2015 sports events in the United Kingdom|Rugby World Cup 2015]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|8th Rugby World Cup}}\n{{Redirect|Rugby World Cup 2015|the video game based on the rugby event|Rugby World Cup 2015 (video game)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox Rugby World Cup\n| logo = File:2015 Rugby World Cup.svg\n| logosize = 220px\n| datefrom = 18 September\n| dateto = 31 October (44 days)\n| host = England\n| nations = 20 (96 qualifying)\n| champion = New Zealand\n| runnerup = Australia\n| third = South Africa\n| matches = 48\n| attendance = 2477805\n| top scorer = {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Nicol\u00e1s S\u00e1nchez (rugby union)|Nicol\u00e1s S\u00e1nchez]] (97)\n| most tries = {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Julian Savea]] (8)\n| preceded by = [[2011 Rugby World Cup|2011]]\n| succeeded by = [[2019 Rugby World Cup|2019]]\n}}\nThe '''2015 Rugby World Cup''' was the eighth [[Rugby World Cup]], the quadrennial [[rugby union]] world championship. The tournament was hosted by [[England]]{{refn|group=nb|name=host|Although England, with its governing body the [[Rugby Football Union]], was officially the sole \"host nation\" of the tournament, some matches were played in [[Cardiff]], Wales.}} from 18 September to 31 October.<ref>{{cite news |title=September 18 start date for RWC 2015 |url=http://rugbywc15.com/england-rugby-world-cup-fixtures-2015-schedule/ |publisher=International Rugby Board |date=15 May 2012 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621005947/http://rugbywc15.com/england-rugby-world-cup-fixtures-2015-schedule/ |archivedate=21 June 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Of the 20 countries competing in the World Cup in 2011, there was only one change: [[Uruguay national rugby union team|Uruguay]] replaced [[Russia national rugby union team|Russia]]. This was the first World Cup with no new teams to the tournament.\n\nReigning champions [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]] won the cup and defended their title by defeating [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] in the final 34\u201317; [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]] defeated [[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina]] to take third place. This was the first Rugby World Cup where no Northern Hemisphere team got beyond the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rugby World Cup 2015: Rugby Championship downs Six Nations|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11531305|publisher=New Zealand Herald|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> New Zealand were the first team to retain their title and the first to win for a third time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/oct/31/new-zealand-australia-rugby-world-cup-final-match-report|title=New Zealand retain Rugby World Cup with ruthless display against Australia|date=31 October 2015|work=Guardian|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe highly contested [[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool B#South Africa vs Japan|match between Japan and South Africa]] on the opening weekend, in which Japan scored the winning try in the final minute, was widely considered the biggest upset in the history of rugby.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/rugby-union/34269878 |title=Rugby World Cup 2015: South Africa 32\u201334 Japan |date=19 September 2015 |accessdate=19 September 2015 }}</ref> Hosts England were eliminated at the pool stage, after defeats by Wales and Australia; this was the first time the sole host nation had failed to progress to the knockout stage.\n\n==Host selection==\n{{See also|Rugby World Cup hosts}}\n\n===Submission of interest===\nThe [[World Rugby|International Rugby Board]] (IRB) requested that any member unions wishing to host this tournament or the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]] should indicate their interest by 15 August 2008. This would be purely to indicate interest; no details had to be provided at this stage. A record 10 unions indicated formal interest in hosting the 2015 and/or the 2019 events: Australia, England, Ireland, Italy, Jamaica, Japan, Russia, Scotland, South Africa and Wales.<ref>BBC Sport, IRB confirm 2015 & 2019 host bids, 25 August 2008, {{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/7564403.stm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151027110739/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/7564403.stm |archivedate=27 October 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> Argentina had been reported in early 2008 as having given preliminary consideration to bidding,<ref>{{cite news |title=Argentina se postul\u00f3 para organizar el Mundial 2015 |url=http://www.rugbytime.com/noticia.php?id=2957 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528092401/http://www.rugbytime.com/noticia.php?id=2957 |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 May 2012 |work=rugbytime.com |publisher=RugbyTime.com |date=26 February 2008 |accessdate=11 October 2011}}</ref> but did not ultimately formally indicate an interest in bidding.\n\nOf the 10 nations that had expressed formal interest, many withdrew their candidacy in early 2009. Jamaica was the first to withdraw its candidacy.<ref name=\"rugbyworldcup1\">IRB, England and Japan handed Rugby World Cups, 28 July 2009, {{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/rugbyworldcup2019/news/newsid=2053414.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111033037/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/rugbyworldcup2019/news/newsid%3D2053414.html |archivedate=11 November 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> Russia withdrew in February 2009 to concentrate on bidding for the [[2013 Rugby World Cup Sevens]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Russia keen to bid for RWC Sevens 2013 |url=http://www.rwcsevens.com/home/news/newsid=2029106.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527124305/http://www.rwcsevens.com/home/news/newsid%3D2029106.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 May 2011 |work=IRB.com |publisher=International Rugby Board |accessdate=15 February 2009 }}</ref> Australia and Ireland withdrew in spring 2009 due to financial reasons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ireland opt out of 2015 bidding |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/8029212.stm |date=1 May 2009 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=6 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504054052/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/8029212.stm |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Australia ends 2015 World Cup bid |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/8009032.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 April 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423073310/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/8009032.stm |archivedate=23 April 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland withdrew in April 2009 after they were unable to secure co-hosting partners for the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scotland pull out of RWC 2015 bid |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/8025810.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=29 April 2009 |accessdate=29 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430012304/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/8025810.stm |archivedate=30 April 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wales was the last nation to officially pull out after they failed to submit a bid by 8 May 2009,<ref>{{cite news |title=IRB confirms record RWC bid response |url=http://www.irb.com/newsmedia/mediazone/pressrelease/newsid=2031234.html |work=IRB.com |publisher=International Rugby Board |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=9 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511095243/http://www.irb.com/newsmedia/mediazone/pressrelease/newsid%3D2031234.html |archivedate=11 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> but Wales backed England's bid and some games were played at Cardiff's [[Millennium Stadium]].<ref name=Millennium>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/13533375.stm |title=Millennium Stadium chosen as 2015 Rugby World Cup venue |work=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2011 |accessdate=24 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Final bids===\nThe final nations that bid for the right to host the 2015 Rugby World Cup were England, Japan, South Africa and Italy. Four confirmed bids was a record number for the Rugby World Cup.<ref name=\"rugbyworldcup1\" />\n\nOn 28 July 2009, the IRB confirmed that England would host the 2015 Rugby World Cup, and Japan would host the 2019 event,<ref name=\"host\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/rugby-world-cup/5926689/England-2015-will-be-best-Rugby-World-Cup-ever-says-RFU-chief-Francis-Baron.html |title=England 2015 will be best Rugby World Cup ever, says RFU chief Francis Baron |date=28 July 2009 |work=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=20 November 2013 |location=London}}</ref> having voted 16\u201310 in favour of approving the recommendation from Rugby World Cup Ltd (RWCL) that England and Japan should be named hosts.{{refn|group=nb|The IRB became World Rugby on 19 November 2014.<ref>{{cite press release|title=IRB to change name to World Rugby |url=http://www.irb.com/newsmedia/mediazone/pressrelease/newsid=2072837.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903113040/http://www.irb.com/newsmedia/mediazone/pressrelease/newsid%3D2072837.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 September 2014 |publisher=International Rugby Board |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=28 August 2014 }}</ref> However, the 2015 World Cup retained its IRB branding, given the proximity of the rebrand to the event, and as merchandise was already available with IRB branding at the time of the name change. The 2019 Rugby World Cup was the first to use full World Rugby branding.}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/8126952.stm |title=England set to get 2015 World Cup |date=30 June 2009 |accessdate=30 June 2009 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] }}</ref> RWCL chairman [[Bernard Lapasset]] revealed the result on 28 July 2009 at IRB headquarters.<ref name=\"host\">{{cite news |title=England will host 2015 World Cup |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/8170488.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=28 July 2009 |accessdate=28 July 2009 }}</ref>\n\n====England====\nIn September 2007, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that the Rugby Football Union had decided to submit a bid. BBC News reported in February 2009 that the intent was for a solo bid from the RFU, but with the possibility of some matches being played in Scotland, Wales or Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |title=England to make solo 2015 Cup bid |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7898571.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=19 February 2009 |accessdate=20 February 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222092455/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7898571.stm |archivedate=22 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was hoped that the 2015 World Cup would add to Britain's \"[[Major sports event hosting in Britain during the 2010s|Decade of Sport]]\" (including the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], [[2013 Rugby League World Cup]] and [[2014 Commonwealth Games]]).\n\nIt was also claimed that the bid had a very strong chance of success due to the IRB's belief that the 2011 tournament might make a loss, therefore making it particularly important to ensure a profit, which was considered a strong point of England's proposed bid.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://sport.guardian.co.uk/rugbyworldcup2007/story/0,,2160211,00.html |work=The Guardian |location=London |title=England can bank on 2015 cup as board pushes for profit |first=Paul |last=Rees |date=1 September 2007 |accessdate=23 April 2010 }}</ref> The chief executive of the [[Rugby Football Union]], Francis Baron, said that the tournament would target sales of 3&nbsp;million tickets. England's package was projected to generate \u00a3300m for the IRB \u2013 \u00a3220m in commercial returns from broadcasting, sponsorship and merchandising, and the \u00a380m tournament fee.<ref name=\"host\" />\n\n====Italy====\nItaly stated its desire to host,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2007/09/02/srbate102.xml |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |title=Diego Dominguez ready for Rugby World Cup |first=Rupert |last=Bates |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=23 April 2010 }}</ref> and an Italian bid to host the [[Rugby World Cup]] in 2015 or 2019 was confirmed on 20 July 2008. Italy declared that it wanted to host \"For the Enlargement of the Frontiers of Our Sport\". It was a slogan relevant to the then-current landscape of World Cup rugby, given that 2007 was the first time that the Rugby World Cup was hosted by a primarily non-[[English-speaking country]].\n\nThe Italian bid offered the largest cities and stadiums in the country and promised a fast domestic train system. The [[Italian Rugby Federation]] (FIR) also included the importance of the population and the growth of rugby since Italy joined the [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] in 2000 as reasons for hosting a World Cup. Rugby had been growing increasingly popular in Italy in recent years, with improved crowds at international matches.\n\nThe [[Stadio Olimpico]] in Rome had been proposed as the venue to host the final and the first match of the tournament. Milan and Naples were included as the other large venues. The entire list was a selection of large stadiums spread across the country. [[Stade V\u00e9lodrome]] in [[Marseille]], France was also included as the tenth proposed venue.\n\n====Japan====\n{{Main article|2019 Rugby World Cup}}\n\nThe [[Japan Rugby Football Union]] officially submitted its tender to the IRB in May 2009.<ref name=\"Japan joins\" /> Japan was seen as a favourite to host after finishing as runner-up in the bidding for the 2011 event.<ref name=\"Japan joins\">[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/08/japan-rugby-world-cup-england-south-africa Japan joins England and South Africa in bidding for Rugby World Cup] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303175301/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/08/japan-rugby-world-cup-england-south-africa |date=3 March 2016 }}, guardian.co.uk, 8 May 2009</ref> Japan was seen as having a lot to offer rugby's growth in Asia.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} Its population of 127&nbsp;million, its large economy, and its ability to place rugby before a new Asian audience made it a front-runner for hosting rights.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} Furthermore, rugby in Japan had developed a following, and with 126,000 registered players, Japan had more players than some of the Six Nations.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} Japan's [[Top League]] was a showcase for Japanese rugby, and there was excitement about Japan's entry into the RWC.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} Japan's experience in co-hosting the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] was also seen as a boost, with Japan already possessing the necessary stadiums and infrastructure.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n====South Africa====\nThe South African Rugby Union (SARU) had confirmed its intent to bid for the 2015 tournament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mattsports.co.uk/blog/30000-tickets-more-on-sale-for-rugby-wc-2015/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920232501/http://mattsports.co.uk/blog/30000-tickets-more-on-sale-for-rugby-wc-2015/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 September 2015 |title=30,000 Tickets More on Sale for Rugby WC 2015 |work=mattsports.co.uk }}</ref> and in May 2009 South Africa delivered its application to the IRB.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/8037903.stm |title=South Africa bids for World Cup |date=7 May 2009 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=7 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508012256/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/8037903.stm |archivedate=8 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> South Africa had previously made an unsuccessful bid to host the 2011 RWC. The strengths of a South African bid would be that it is in the same time zone as Europe, the wealthiest television market from a rugby perspective, that South Africa were the current World Cup holders, that they had successfully hosted the [[1995 Rugby World Cup]], won the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] and that they were in the process of building large new stadiums for the then-upcoming [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Venues==\nAfter England were appointed tournament hosts on 28 July 2009, the proposed stadia for the tournament were revealed. The final venues were confirmed, along with the tournament's schedule, on 2 May 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=RWC 2015 venues and schedule announced |url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/home/news/newsid=2066509.html |work=rugbyworldcup.com |publisher=International Rugby Board |date=2 May 2013 |accessdate=2 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507111825/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/home/news/newsid%3D2066509.html |archivedate=7 May 2013 }}</ref> Twelve of the stadia were located in England, while the [[Millennium Stadium]] located in neighbour Wales was also to be used. In 2011, the IRB approved the use of the Millennium Stadium, despite being outside of the host country, due to its capacity and strategic location.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/wales/rugby/story/140367.html |title=Millennium Stadium confirmed as RWC'15 venue |work=ESPN Scrum |date=24 May 2011 |accessdate=24 May 2011}}</ref> Of the thirteen venues, two were dedicated rugby union grounds ([[Kingsholm Stadium]] and [[Sandy Park]]), two were national rugby stadia ([[Twickenham Stadium|Twickenham]] and the Millennium Stadium), two were multi-purpose stadia ([[Wembley Stadium]] and the [[London Stadium|Olympic Stadium]]), and the remainder were association football grounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/england/5926074/Rugby-World-Cup-guide-to-England-2015-stadiums.html|title=Rugby World Cup: guide to England 2015 stadiums |date=28 June 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=16 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114060444/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/england/5926074/Rugby-World-Cup-guide-to-England-2015-stadiums.html |archivedate=14 November 2010 |url-status=live |location=London}}</ref>\n\nProposed venues that did not make the final selection were the [[Stadium of Light]] in [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]], [[Coventry]]'s [[Ricoh Arena]], [[St Mary's Stadium]] in [[Southampton]], [[Pride Park Stadium]] in [[Derby]], [[Anfield]] in Liverpool and [[Bristol]]'s [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/rugby-world-cup/9595617/Rugby-World-Cup-2015-long-list-of-potential-venues-named-but-Leicesters-Welford-Road-left-out.html |title=Rugby World Cup 2015 Long list of potential venues |date=9 October 2009 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London}}</ref> In April 2013, [[Old Trafford]] was withdrawn from consideration by its owners, [[Manchester United F.C.]], citing commitments to hosting [[rugby league]] and its [[Super League Grand Final]] and concerns about pitch degradation. The RWCL then approached neighbouring [[Manchester City]] about leasing [[City of Manchester Stadium|their home stadium]] as a replacement. City agreed to let their stadium be used for the tournament but only for one match due to footballing commitments \u2013 down from the original three which were to be played at Old Trafford.<ref>{{cite news |title=2015 Rugby World Cup can only persuade Manchester City to host one game |last=Rumsby |first=Ben |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/england/9970460/2015-Rugby-World-Cup-can-only-persuade-Manchester-City-to-host-one-game.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=4 April 2013 |location=London}}</ref> Etihad Stadium, as it was known for football sponsorship purposes, would be called 'Manchester City Stadium' by organisers for the duration of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=RWC 2015 venues and schedule announced |url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/home/news/newsid=2066509.html |date=2 May 2013 |accessdate=17 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111033040/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/home/news/newsid%3D2066509.html |archivedate=11 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! {{flagicon|ENG}} [[London]]\n! colspan=2|{{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[London]]'''\n! colspan=2|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[London]]\n! {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Cardiff]]\n|-\n|[[Wembley Stadium]]\n|colspan=2|'''[[Twickenham Stadium|Twickenham]]'''\n|colspan=2|[[London Stadium|Olympic Stadium]]\n|[[Millennium Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''90,000'''\n|colspan=2|Capacity: '''82,000'''\n|colspan=2|Capacity: '''56,000'''\n|Capacity: '''74,154'''\n|-\n|[[File:Wembley Stadium 2015 RWC.jpg|180px]]\n|colspan=2|[[File:2015 Rugby World Cup, Australia vs. Wales (21485242524) (cropped).jpg|180px]]\n|colspan=2|[[File:Olympic Stadium (London) rugby layout.jpg|180px]]\n|[[File:Millennium Stadium RWC2015.jpg|180px]]\n|-\n! {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]]\n!rowspan=8 colspan=4|\n{{Location map+ |England |float=center |width=400 |length=800 |c