0e9ric Michalak|Michalak]] (4)\n|pen1=[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Michalak|Michalak]] (5)\n|try2=[[Kevin Maggs|Maggs]] 52' c<br />[[Brian O'Driscoll|O'Driscoll]] (2) 65' c, 80+2' c\n|con2=[[David Humphreys (rugby player)|Humphreys]] (3)\n|stadium=Docklands Stadium, Melbourne\n|attendance=33,134\n|referee=[[Jonathan Kaplan (rugby referee)|Jonathan Kaplan]] ([[South African Rugby Union|South Africa]])\n}}\n----\n{{Rugbybox\n|date=9 November 2003\n|home={{Ru-rt|ENG}}\n|score=28\u201317\n|away={{Ru|WAL}}\n|try1=[[Will Greenwood|Greenwood]] 44' c\n|con1=[[Jonny Wilkinson|Wilkinson]]\n|pen1=[[Jonny Wilkinson|Wilkinson]] (6)\n|drop1=[[Jonny Wilkinson|Wilkinson]] 80+1'\n|try2=[[Stephen Jones (rugby player)|S. Jones]] 30' m<br />[[Colin Charvis|Charvis]] 35' m<br />[[Martyn Williams|M. Williams]] 71' c\n|con2=[[Iestyn Harris|Harris]]\n|stadium=[[Suncorp Stadium]], [[Brisbane]]\n|attendance=45,252\n|referee=[[Alain Rolland]] ([[Irish Rugby Football Union|Ireland]])\n}}\n\n===Semi-finals===\n{{Rugbybox\n|date=15 November 2003\n|home={{Ru-rt|NZL}}\n|score=10\u201322\n|away={{Ru|AUS}}\n|try1=[[Reuben Thorne|Thorne]] 35' c\n|con1=[[Leon MacDonald|MacDonald]]\n|pen1=[[Leon MacDonald|MacDonald]]\n|try2=[[Stirling Mortlock|Mortlock]] 9' c\n|con2=[[Elton Flatley|Flatley]]\n|pen2=[[Elton Flatley|Flatley]] (5)\n|stadium=Stadium Australia, Sydney\n|attendance=82,444\n|referee=[[Chris White (referee)|Chris White]] ([[Rugby Football Union|England]])\n}}\n----\n{{Rugbybox\n|date=16 November 2003\n|home={{Ru-rt|FRA}}\n|score=7\u201324\n|away={{Ru|ENG}}\n|try1=[[Serge Betsen|Betsen]] 10' c\n|con1=[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Michalak|Michalak]]\n|pen2=[[Jonny Wilkinson|Wilkinson]] (5)\n|drop2=[[Jonny Wilkinson|Wilkinson]] (3) 9', 38', 58'\n|stadium=Stadium Australia, Sydney\n|attendance=82,346\n|referee=[[Paddy O'Brien (rugby referee)|Paddy O'Brien]] ([[New Zealand Rugby Union|New Zealand]])\n}}\n\n===Third-place play-off===\n{{Rugbybox\n|date=20 November 2003\n|home={{Ru-rt|NZL}}\n|score=40\u201313\n|away={{Ru|FRA}}\n|try1=[[Chris Jack|Jack]] 12' c<br />[[Doug Howlett|Howlett]] 20' c<br />[[Joe Rokocoko|Rokocoko]] 51' c<br />[[Brad Thorn|Thorn]] 54' c<br />[[Mils Muliaina|Muliaina]] 58' c<br />[[Marty Holah|Holah]] 72' m\n|con1=[[Leon MacDonald|MacDonald]]<br />[[Dan Carter|Carter]] (4)\n|try2=[[P\u00e9pito Elhorga|Elhorga]] 42' c\n|con2=[[Dimitri Yachvili|Yachvili]]\n|pen2=[[Dimitri Yachvili|Yachvili]]\n|drop2=[[Dimitri Yachvili|Yachvili]]\n|stadium=Stadium Australia, Sydney\n|attendance=62,712\n|referee=[[Chris White (referee)|Chris White]] ([[Rugby Football Union|England]])\n}}\n\n===Final===\n{{main|2003 Rugby World Cup Final}}\n{{Rugbybox\n|date=22 November 2003\n|home={{Ru-rt|AUS}}\n|score=17\u201320 ([[Extra time|a.e.t.]])\n|report=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/international/3228728.stm Report]\n|away={{Ru|ENG}}\n|try1=[[Lote Tuqiri|Tuqiri]] 6' m\n|pen1=[[Elton Flatley|Flatley]] (4)\n|try2=[[Jason Robinson (rugby player)|Robinson]] 38' m\n|pen2=[[Jonny Wilkinson|Wilkinson]] (4)\n|drop2=[[Jonny Wilkinson|Wilkinson]] 100'\n|stadium=Stadium Australia, Sydney\n|attendance=82,957\n|referee=[[Andr\u00e9 Watson]] ([[South African Rugby Union|South Africa]])\n}}\n\n==Statistics==\n{{main|2003 Rugby World Cup statistics}}\n\nThe tournament's top point scorer was England's [[Jonny Wilkinson]], who scored 113 points. [[Doug Howlett]] and [[Mils Muliaina]] scored the most tries, seven in total.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+\n|-\n!width=145|Player\n!width=145|Team\n!width=100|Position\n!width=40|Played\n!width=40|Tries\n!width=40|Conv{{shy}}ersions\n!width=40|Penal{{shy}}ties\n!width=40|Drop goals\n!width=40|Total points\n!width=40|Yellow cards\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Jonny Wilkinson]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|ENG}}\n|[[Fly-half (rugby union)|Fly-half]]\n|6||0||10||23||8||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''113'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Michalak]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|FRA}}\n|[[Fly-half (rugby union)|Fly-half]]\n|6||2||17||18||1||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''101'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Elton Flatley]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|AUS}}\n|[[Centre (rugby union)|Centre]]\n|6||1||16||21||0||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''100'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Leon MacDonald]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|NZL}}\n|[[Centre (rugby union)|Centre]]\n|7||4||20||5||0||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''75'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Chris Paterson]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|SCO}}\n|[[Fly-half (rugby union)|Fly-half]]\n|5||3||7||13||1||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''71'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Mat Rogers]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|AUS}}\n|[[Fullback (rugby union)|Full-back]]\n|7||5||16||0||0||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''57'''||1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Mike Hercus]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{nowrap|{{Ru|USA}}}}\n|[[Fly-half (rugby union)|Fly-half]]\n|4||2||7||9||0||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''51'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Rima Wakarua]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|ITA}}\n|[[Fly-half (rugby union)|Fly-half]]\n|3||0||4||14||0||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''50'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Earl Va'a]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|SAM}}\n|[[Fly-half (rugby union)|Fly-half]]\n|4||1||10||8||0||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''49'''||0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Dan Carter]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Ru|NZL}}\n|[[Fly-half (rugby union)|Fly-half]]\n|5||2||19||0||0||! scope=row style=\"background:#ccc\"|'''48'''||0\n|}\n\n==Broadcasters==\nThe event was broadcast by [[Seven Network]] and [[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] in [[Australia]] and by [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|2003 Rugby World Cup}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060507172716/http://www.rwc2003.irb.com/EN 2003 Rugby World Cup Official site] (Archived)\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/rugby_world_cup/fixtures_/default.stm 2003 Rugby World Cup Reports and Statistics]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/rugby_world_cup/3229102.stm BBC account of 2003 World Cup victory]\n*[http://www.espnscrum.com/2011-rugby-world-cup/rugby/series/18666.html Tournament Results & Statistics] on ESPN Scrum\n\n{{2003 Rugby World Cup}}\n{{2003 Rugby World Cup finalists}}\n{{2003 Rugby World Cup venues}}\n{{2003 Rugby World Cup referees}}\n{{Rugby Union World Cup}}\n\n[[Category:2003 Rugby World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:Rugby World Cup tournaments]]\n[[Category:International rugby union competitions hosted by Australia|World Cup]]\n[[Category:October 2003 sports events]]\n[[Category:November 2003 sports events]]\n[[Category:2003 in Australian rugby union]]\n", "name_user": "176.25.204.200", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2003_Rugby_World_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Breathless Mahoney", "text_new": "{{short description|Femme fatale character in the American comic strip Dick Tracy}}\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image =\n|caption =\n|character_name = Breathless Mahoney\n|publisher = [[Tribune Media Services]]\n|debut = May 11, 1945\n|last =\n|creators = [[Chester Gould]]\n|alter_ego =\n|base of operations =\n|alliances = \n|aliases =\n|supports= \n|powers = \n}}\n'''''Breathless Mahoney''''' is a [[femme fatale]] in the American [[comic strip]] ''[[Dick Tracy]]'' which was created by [[Chester Gould]] in 1931.<ref>[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/annie-missing-no-worries-dick-tracy-is-on-the-case/?_r=0 The New York Times]</ref><ref>[http://www.ew.com/gallery/13-mob-molls-moxie-moviestv/654905_breathless-mahoney-dick-tracy Entertainment Weekly]</ref><ref>[http://www.comicvine.com/breathless-mahoney/4005-9889/ Comicvine.com]</ref> She first appeared in the strip on May 11, 1945,<ref>''The Complete Dick Tracy, Volume 9'' by Chester Gould, IDW Publishing (2009)</ref> and was apparently killed on August 26, 1946.<ref>''The Complete Dick Tracy, Volume 10'' by Chester Gould, IDW Publishing (2010)</ref>\n\nThe character found worldwide fame in 1990 in the much-hyped ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' film, as a villainous nightclub singer played by pop superstar [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. The character's glamorous outfits, described extensively in the press, sparked a brief fad for 1940s fashion.\n\n==Comic strip character==\nBreathless Mahoney was created by [[Chester Gould]] and introduced to the ''[[Dick Tracy]]'' comic strip on May 10, 1945.<ref name=\"Roberts105\">{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=105}}</ref><ref name=\"Roberts279\">{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=279}}</ref> Garyn G. Roberts, author of ''Dick Tracy and American Culture: Morality and Mythology, Text and Context'', noted that the introduction of Breathless coincided with Gould's efforts to \"integrate characters and episodes with a sophistication that would mark the 1950s ''Tracy'' continuities\".<ref name=\"Roberts105\" /> The character was illustrated as an attractive young blonde intended to resemble actress [[Veronica Lake]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|pp=105\u2013106}}</ref> Breathless is portrayed as greedy and obsessed with money, willing to commit murder to obtain it. She is the stepdaughter of [[List of Dick Tracy villains|Shaky]], a ''Dick Tracy'' antagonist who had recently been killed in the storyline; she discovers his skeletal remains near the waterfront in one of the strips.<ref name=\"Roberts106\">{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=106}}</ref> Writer Meredith M. Malburne-Wade said the character is named \"Breathless\" because \"she both speaks in a breathy voice meant to pull others closer to her and strives to leave the men around her breathless in her wake\".<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\">{{Harvnb|Malburne-Wade|2019|p=79}}</ref>\n\nThe original comic strip version of Breathless Mahoney is depicted as a ruthless and psychopathic killer, in contrast to the character's more sympathetic later version in the ''1990'' film adaptation of ''Dick Tracy''.<ref name=\"Roberts279\" /><ref name=\"Lukinbeal\">{{cite journal |last1=Lukinbeal |first1=Christopher L. |last2=Kennedy |first2=Christina B. |title=Dick Tracy's Cityscape |journal=Yearbook of the Association of Pacific Coast Geographers |date=1993 |volume=55 |pages=76-96 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24040084?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=%22breathless+mahoney%22&searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3D%2522breathless%2Bmahoney%2522&ab_segments=0%2Fbasic_SYC-5055%2Ftest&refreqid=search%3Ac35abfa6a0c9e6a43dbd2123df03deb0&seq=14#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> At one point, she stabs a man in the back with a pair of pruning shears.<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> During one of her storylines, Breathless encounters [[List of Dick Tracy characters#Personal acquaintances|B.O. Plenty]], an unkempt [[hillbilly]]-like character who schemes to steal her money.<ref name=\"Roberts106\" /> Roberts said of this storyline: \"The conflict between the physically beautiful villainess and the unwashed country bumpkin makes for entertaining reading.\"<ref name=\"Roberts106\" /> Breathless made her final appearance in a ''Dick Tracy'' comic strip on August 25, 1946, in which the character died. Just before her death, while laying in a hospital bed, she wrote a final letter forgiving B.O. Plenty for past issues she had with him.<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|pp=279\u2013280}}</ref>\n\n==1990 movie==\nBreathless Mahoney appears in the film adaptation ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' (1990),<ref>{{cite news |last=Canby |first=Vincent |title=Review/FIlm;   A Cartoon Square Comes to Life In 'Dick Tracy' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 15, 1990 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/15/movies/review-film-a-cartoon-square-comes-to-life-in-dick-tracy.html |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Brunsdale|2010|p=683}}</ref> in which she is portrayed by actress and singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Dick Tracy (1990) Review/FIlm; A Cartoon Square Comes to Life In 'Dick Tracy'|author=Canby, Vincent|authorlink=Vincent Canby|date=June 15, 1990|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CEFD8153DF936A25755C0A966958260|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/06/dick-tracy-25th-anniversary Vanity Fair]</ref><ref>[http://www.ew.com/article/1990/05/25/im-breathless-music-and-inspired-film-dick-tracy Entertainment Weekly]</ref>  The film character differs from the original comic strip counterpart, most notably in her profession as a nightclub singer.<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> She is also less violent and psychopathic that the comic strip version of the character,<ref name=\"Roberts279\" /><ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> more calculating in her actions, and is revealed to be as intelligent as Dick Tracy himself.<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> Writers Christopher L. Lukinbeal and Cristina B. Kennedy wrote of the character: \"Breathless, in the film, provides a complex, more 1980s, opposition of good and evil, moral and amoral.\"<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> In another difference from the source material, Breathless was not introduced in the comic strip until 1945, but the film is set in the 1930s. She is one of several characters in the film who was introduced in the 1940s in the comic, along with 88 Keyes and Sam Catchem.<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=281}}</ref> Breathless Mahoney also disguises herself in the film as a villain known as \"The Blank\", wearing a mask that makes her appear to have no face. This is another deviation from the original character; The Blank was a character in the original ''Dick Tracy'' comic strip, but he was not associated with Breathless Mahoney at all.{{fact|date=February 2020}} Madonna, who was dating ''Dick Tracy'' star and director [[Warren Beatty]] at the time, sought the role of Breathless, but offered to work for scale to avoid the perception of [[nepotism]], earning just $35,000 for the film.<ref>{{Harvnb|Thakur|2010|p=198}}</ref><ref name=week>{{cite news | author = [[David Ansen]]; Pamela Abramson | url = http://www.newsweek.com/id/127653 | title = Tracymania | work = [[Newsweek]] | date = June 25, 1990 | accessdate = April 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn the film, Breathless is portrayed as a ''[[femme fatale]]'',<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /><ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\" /> and as Lukinbeal and Kennedy note: \"Where Tracy represents day, she represents night. While Tracy fights to protect the city from evil, Breathless is only concerned with her own future and, like Big Boy Caprice, with her desire to \"own\" the city.\"<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> The song \"More\", which Breathless sings at a nightclub, is symbolic of her plans to own the city, according to writer Steve Swayne. On the surface, it sounds like a song about a flirtatious woman who can never get enough, but Swayne said it in fact symbolizes her secret plan to trap Big Boy Caprice and take over his criminal operation. The fact that Breathless continues to sing the song unabated in the nightclub while Big Boy's men engage in a shootout with the police, due to events Breathless herself put into motion, only further underscore this.<ref name=\"Swayne\">{{cite journal |last1=Swayne |first1=Steve |title=So Much \"More\": The Music of \"Dick Tracy\" (1990) |journal=American Music |date=Spring 2004 |volume=22 |issue=1 |page=60 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3592966?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=breathless&searchText=mahoney&searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3Dbreathless%2Bmahoney%26amp%3Bacc%3Doff%26amp%3Bwc%3Don%26amp%3Bfc%3Doff%26amp%3Bgroup%3Dnone&ab_segments=0%2Fbasic_SYC-5055%2Ftest&refreqid=search%3Ad26d76fa5aebfbc1c465608314c636ff&seq=11#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> Breathless is portrayed as Dick Tracy's temptress in the film, providing as a stark contrast against his girlfriend Tess Truehart, who represents the more pure and clean-cut choice.<ref name=\"Sandow0525\" /><ref>{{Harvnb|Malburne-Wade|2019|p=78}}</ref>\n\nIn the book ''The Encyclopedia of Sexism in American Films'', Meredith M. Malburne-Wade writes that Breathless and Tess \"occupy predominantly standard (and stereotypical) roles for women\".<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\" /> She also wrote: \"The two women seem, on the surface, to clearly occupy opposite sidse of the angel/whore or angel/monster dichotomy set out by many feminist and literary critics. ... Mahoney is the monster/whore, posing as a man, flaunting her body and sexuality, and ultimately challenging men who try to control her.\"<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\" /> She says Breathless' advances on Dick Tracy and others in the film stereotypically suggest men are simply victims of sexually-available women. However, Malburne-Wade also notes that both Breathless and Tess are \"largely constrained by masculinity and by love\" in the film,<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\" /> and that Breathless has little control herself over the direction of her own life, which is instead dictated by the actions of gangsters like Lips Manlis and Big Boy Caprice, the latter of whom is physically abusive toward her.<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\">{{Harvnb|Malburne-Wade|2019|p=80}}</ref> She writes: \"The fact that her sexuality is her only bargaining chip \u2013 and one that is as likely to get her beaten as it is to get her kissed \u2013 suggests a brutally patriarchal world.\"<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\" /> The only time she holds power over her own destiny is when she disguises herself as a man: The Blank.<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\" /> In the book ''Madonna as Postmodern Myth'', Georges-Claude Guilbert writes that in ''Dick Tracy'', Madonna's Breathless Mahoney \"is a bad girl because in a macho world, women in power are disturbing\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=100}}</ref>\n\nGaryn G. Roberts wrote that Madonna's established image as a singer and celebrity \"played well into the character of Breathless Mahoney; her singing was one of several highlights of the motion picture production\".<ref name=\"Roberts279\" /> Madonna, in character as Breathless Mahoney, sings several songs in the ''Dick Tracy'' film. Many of these songs were included in the [[soundtrack album]] Madonna released called ''[[I'm Breathless]]'' (1990), which was also named after the character.<ref name=\"Sandow0525\">{{cite news |last=Sandow |first=Greg |title=I'm Breathless: Music from and Inspired by the Film Dick Tracy |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=May 25, 1990 |url=https://ew.com/article/1990/05/25/im-breathless-music-and-inspired-film-dick-tracy/ |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Among the songs is a duet of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s \"What Can You Lose\" between Breathless and 88 Keys ([[Mandy Patinkin]]).<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=279}}</ref> Others include the song \"More\",<ref name=\"Swayne\" /> and \"[[Sooner or Later (Madonna song)|Sooner or Later]]\", both of which Madonna sings in character as Breathless, and the latter of which went on to win the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Warren Beatty's 'Dick Tracy' on Blu-ray for first time |work=[[USA Today]] |date=December 15, 2012 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2012/12/14/dick-tracy-warren-beatty/1764813/ |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> In a review of ''I'm Breathless'' for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Greg Sandow noted that Breathless' role as a temptress in the film resulted in Madonna \"pushing sexual barriers farther than ever in ''I'm Breathless''\".<ref name=\"Sandow0525\" />\n\nFollowing the release of the film, several companies began developing garments inspired by Breathless' character.<ref name=\"Herman\">{{cite news |last1=Herman |first1=Valli |title=Dick Tracy inspires some arresting looks |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/564720672/?terms=breathless%2Bmahoney |accessdate=28 February 2020 |publisher=The Lancaster Intelligencer Journal |date=May 15, 1990}}</ref><ref name=\"Johnson\">{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Marilyn |title=Fashion detectives can track down 1940s duds |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/573197001/?terms=breathless%2Bmahoney |accessdate=28 February 2020 |publisher=Oceanside North County Times |date=May 30, 1990}}</ref> For example, the [[Los Angeles]] company L.A. Glo created a dress collection inspired by Breathless, with dress costs ranging from $70 to $180.<ref name=\"Herman\" /><ref name=\"Johnson\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Homan |first1=Becky |title=Not Left Breathless: Tracy's Fashion Statement Makes Barely a Whisper |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/141296236/?terms=breathless%2Bmahoney |accessdate=28 February 2020 |publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=July 12, 1990}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* {{cite book |last=Brunsdale |first=Mitzi M. |title=Icons of Mystery and Crime Detection: From Sleuths to Superheroes) |year=2010 |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]] |isbn=0313345309 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Guilbert |first=Georges-Claude |title=Madonna As Postmodern Myth: How One Star's Self-Construction Rewrites Sex, Gender, Hollywood and the American Dream |year=2002 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=0786414081 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Malburne-Wade |first=Meredith M. |title=The Encyclopedia of Sexism in American Films |year=2019 |editor1-last=Murgu\u00eda |editor1-first=Salvador Jimenez |editor2-last=Dymond |editor2-first=Erica Joan |editor3-last=Fennelly |editor3-first=Kristina |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |isbn=1538115514 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Roberts |first=Garyn G. |title=Dick Tracy and American Culture: Morality and Mythology, Text and Context |chapter=Dick Tracy (1990) |year=1993 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=0899508804 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thakur |first=Pradeep |title=Madonna: Unstoppable! |year=2010 |asin=B009AOICHU |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160422151836/http://www.imdb.com/character/ch0012366/ Breathless Mahoney] on [[IMDb]]\n{{Dick Tracy}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahoney, Breathless}}\n[[Category:Dick Tracy characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Film serial characters]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1945]]\n[[Category:Female characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Female film villains]]\n[[Category:Fictional singers]]\n\n\n{{film-char-stub}}\n{{comics-char-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image =\n|caption =\n|character_name = Breathless Mahoney\n|publisher = [[Tribune Media Services]]\n|debut = May 11, 1945\n|last =\n|creators = [[Chester Gould]]\n|alter_ego =\n|base of operations =\n|alliances = \n|aliases =\n|supports= \n|powers = \n}}\n'''''Breathless Mahoney''''' is a [[femme fatale]] in the American [[comic strip]] ''[[Dick Tracy]]'' which was created by [[Chester Gould]] in 1931.<ref>[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/annie-missing-no-worries-dick-tracy-is-on-the-case/?_r=0 The New York Times]</ref><ref>[http://www.ew.com/gallery/13-mob-molls-moxie-moviestv/654905_breathless-mahoney-dick-tracy Entertainment Weekly]</ref><ref>[http://www.comicvine.com/breathless-mahoney/4005-9889/ Comicvine.com]</ref> She first appeared in the strip on May 11, 1945,<ref>''The Complete Dick Tracy, Volume 9'' by Chester Gould, IDW Publishing (2009)</ref> and was apparently killed on August 26, 1946.<ref>''The Complete Dick Tracy, Volume 10'' by Chester Gould, IDW Publishing (2010)</ref>\n\nThe character found worldwide fame in 1990 in the much-hyped ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' film, as a villainous nightclub singer played by pop superstar [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. The character's glamorous outfits, described extensively in the press, sparked a brief fad for 1940s fashion.\n\n==Comic strip character==\nBreathless Mahoney was created by [[Chester Gould]] and introduced to the ''[[Dick Tracy]]'' comic strip on May 10, 1945.<ref name=\"Roberts105\">{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=105}}</ref><ref name=\"Roberts279\">{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=279}}</ref> Garyn G. Roberts, author of ''Dick Tracy and American Culture: Morality and Mythology, Text and Context'', noted that the introduction of Breathless coincided with Gould's efforts to \"integrate characters and episodes with a sophistication that would mark the 1950s ''Tracy'' continuities\".<ref name=\"Roberts105\" /> The character was illustrated as an attractive young blonde intended to resemble actress [[Veronica Lake]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|pp=105\u2013106}}</ref> Breathless is portrayed as greedy and obsessed with money, willing to commit murder to obtain it. She is the stepdaughter of [[List of Dick Tracy villains|Shaky]], a ''Dick Tracy'' antagonist who had recently been killed in the storyline; she discovers his skeletal remains near the waterfront in one of the strips.<ref name=\"Roberts106\">{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=106}}</ref> Writer Meredith M. Malburne-Wade said the character is named \"Breathless\" because \"she both speaks in a breathy voice meant to pull others closer to her and strives to leave the men around her breathless in her wake\".<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\">{{Harvnb|Malburne-Wade|2019|p=79}}</ref>\n\nThe original comic strip version of Breathless Mahoney is depicted as a ruthless and psychopathic killer, in contrast to the character's more sympathetic later version in the ''1990'' film adaptation of ''Dick Tracy''.<ref name=\"Roberts279\" /><ref name=\"Lukinbeal\">{{cite journal |last1=Lukinbeal |first1=Christopher L. |last2=Kennedy |first2=Christina B. |title=Dick Tracy's Cityscape |journal=Yearbook of the Association of Pacific Coast Geographers |date=1993 |volume=55 |pages=76-96 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24040084?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=%22breathless+mahoney%22&searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3D%2522breathless%2Bmahoney%2522&ab_segments=0%2Fbasic_SYC-5055%2Ftest&refreqid=search%3Ac35abfa6a0c9e6a43dbd2123df03deb0&seq=14#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> At one point, she stabs a man in the back with a pair of pruning shears.<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> During one of her storylines, Breathless encounters [[List of Dick Tracy characters#Personal acquaintances|B.O. Plenty]], an unkempt [[hillbilly]]-like character who schemes to steal her money.<ref name=\"Roberts106\" /> Roberts said of this storyline: \"The conflict between the physically beautiful villainess and the unwashed country bumpkin makes for entertaining reading.\"<ref name=\"Roberts106\" /> Breathless made her final appearance in a ''Dick Tracy'' comic strip on August 25, 1946, in which the character died. Just before her death, while laying in a hospital bed, she wrote a final letter forgiving B.O. Plenty for past issues she had with him.<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|pp=279\u2013280}}</ref>\n\n==1990 movie==\nBreathless Mahoney appears in the film adaptation ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' (1990),<ref>{{cite news |last=Canby |first=Vincent |title=Review/FIlm;   A Cartoon Square Comes to Life In 'Dick Tracy' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 15, 1990 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/15/movies/review-film-a-cartoon-square-comes-to-life-in-dick-tracy.html |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Brunsdale|2010|p=683}}</ref> in which she is portrayed by actress and singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Dick Tracy (1990) Review/FIlm; A Cartoon Square Comes to Life In 'Dick Tracy'|author=Canby, Vincent|authorlink=Vincent Canby|date=June 15, 1990|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CEFD8153DF936A25755C0A966958260|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/06/dick-tracy-25th-anniversary Vanity Fair]</ref><ref>[http://www.ew.com/article/1990/05/25/im-breathless-music-and-inspired-film-dick-tracy Entertainment Weekly]</ref>  The film character differs from the original comic strip counterpart, most notably in her profession as a nightclub singer.<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> She is also less violent and psychopathic that the comic strip version of the character,<ref name=\"Roberts279\" /><ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> more calculating in her actions, and is revealed to be as intelligent as Dick Tracy himself.<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> Writers Christopher L. Lukinbeal and Cristina B. Kennedy wrote of the character: \"Breathless, in the film, provides a complex, more 1980s, opposition of good and evil, moral and amoral.\"<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> In another difference from the source material, Breathless was not introduced in the comic strip until 1945, but the film is set in the 1930s. She is one of several characters in the film who was introduced in the 1940s in the comic, along with 88 Keyes and Sam Catchem.<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=281}}</ref> Breathless Mahoney also disguises herself in the film as a villain known as \"The Blank\", wearing a mask that makes her appear to have no face. This is another deviation from the original character; The Blank was a character in the original ''Dick Tracy'' comic strip, but he was not associated with Breathless Mahoney at all.{{fact|date=February 2020}} Madonna, who was dating ''Dick Tracy'' star and director [[Warren Beatty]] at the time, sought the role of Breathless, but offered to work for scale to avoid the perception of [[nepotism]], earning just $35,000 for the film.<ref>{{Harvnb|Thakur|2010|p=198}}</ref><ref name=week>{{cite news | author = [[David Ansen]]; Pamela Abramson | url = http://www.newsweek.com/id/127653 | title = Tracymania | work = [[Newsweek]] | date = June 25, 1990 | accessdate = April 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn the film, Breathless is portrayed as a ''[[femme fatale]]'',<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /><ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\" /> and as Lukinbeal and Kennedy note: \"Where Tracy represents day, she represents night. While Tracy fights to protect the city from evil, Breathless is only concerned with her own future and, like Big Boy Caprice, with her desire to \"own\" the city.\"<ref name=\"Lukinbeal\" /> The song \"More\", which Breathless sings at a nightclub, is symbolic of her plans to own the city, according to writer Steve Swayne. On the surface, it sounds like a song about a flirtatious woman who can never get enough, but Swayne said it in fact symbolizes her secret plan to trap Big Boy Caprice and take over his criminal operation. The fact that Breathless continues to sing the song unabated in the nightclub while Big Boy's men engage in a shootout with the police, due to events Breathless herself put into motion, only further underscore this.<ref name=\"Swayne\">{{cite journal |last1=Swayne |first1=Steve |title=So Much \"More\": The Music of \"Dick Tracy\" (1990) |journal=American Music |date=Spring 2004 |volume=22 |issue=1 |page=60 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3592966?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=breathless&searchText=mahoney&searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3Dbreathless%2Bmahoney%26amp%3Bacc%3Doff%26amp%3Bwc%3Don%26amp%3Bfc%3Doff%26amp%3Bgroup%3Dnone&ab_segments=0%2Fbasic_SYC-5055%2Ftest&refreqid=search%3Ad26d76fa5aebfbc1c465608314c636ff&seq=11#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> Breathless is portrayed as Dick Tracy's temptress in the film, providing as a stark contrast against his girlfriend Tess Truehart, who represents the more pure and clean-cut choice.<ref name=\"Sandow0525\" /><ref>{{Harvnb|Malburne-Wade|2019|p=78}}</ref>\n\nIn the book ''The Encyclopedia of Sexism in American Films'', Meredith M. Malburne-Wade writes that Breathless and Tess \"occupy predominantly standard (and stereotypical) roles for women\".<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\" /> She also wrote: \"The two women seem, on the surface, to clearly occupy opposite sidse of the angel/whore or angel/monster dichotomy set out by many feminist and literary critics. ... Mahoney is the monster/whore, posing as a man, flaunting her body and sexuality, and ultimately challenging men who try to control her.\"<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\" /> She says Breathless' advances on Dick Tracy and others in the film stereotypically suggest men are simply victims of sexually-available women. However, Malburne-Wade also notes that both Breathless and Tess are \"largely constrained by masculinity and by love\" in the film,<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade79\" /> and that Breathless has little control herself over the direction of her own life, which is instead dictated by the actions of gangsters like Lips Manlis and Big Boy Caprice, the latter of whom is physically abusive toward her.<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\">{{Harvnb|Malburne-Wade|2019|p=80}}</ref> She writes: \"The fact that her sexuality is her only bargaining chip \u2013 and one that is as likely to get her beaten as it is to get her kissed \u2013 suggests a brutally patriarchal world.\"<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\" /> The only time she holds power over her own destiny is when she disguises herself as a man: The Blank.<ref name=\"Malburne-Wade80\" /> In the book ''Madonna as Postmodern Myth'', Georges-Claude Guilbert writes that in ''Dick Tracy'', Madonna's Breathless Mahoney \"is a bad girl because in a macho world, women in power are disturbing\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=100}}</ref>\n\nGaryn G. Roberts wrote that Madonna's established image as a singer and celebrity \"played well into the character of Breathless Mahoney; her singing was one of several highlights of the motion picture production\".<ref name=\"Roberts279\" /> Madonna, in character as Breathless Mahoney, sings several songs in the ''Dick Tracy'' film. Many of these songs were included in the [[soundtrack album]] Madonna released called ''[[I'm Breathless]]'' (1990), which was also named after the character.<ref name=\"Sandow0525\">{{cite news |last=Sandow |first=Greg |title=I'm Breathless: Music from and Inspired by the Film Dick Tracy |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=May 25, 1990 |url=https://ew.com/article/1990/05/25/im-breathless-music-and-inspired-film-dick-tracy/ |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Among the songs is a duet of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s \"What Can You Lose\" between Breathless and 88 Keys ([[Mandy Patinkin]]).<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1993|p=279}}</ref> Others include the song \"More\",<ref name=\"Swayne\" /> and \"[[Sooner or Later (Madonna song)|Sooner or Later]]\", both of which Madonna sings in character as Breathless, and the latter of which went on to win the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Warren Beatty's 'Dick Tracy' on Blu-ray for first time |work=[[USA Today]] |date=December 15, 2012 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2012/12/14/dick-tracy-warren-beatty/1764813/ |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> In a review of ''I'm Breathless'' for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Greg Sandow noted that Breathless' role as a temptress in the film resulted in Madonna \"pushing sexual barriers farther than ever in ''I'm Breathless''\".<ref name=\"Sandow0525\" />\n\nFollowing the release of the film, several companies began developing garments inspired by Breathless' character.<ref name=\"Herman\">{{cite news |last1=Herman |first1=Valli |title=Dick Tracy inspires some arresting looks |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/564720672/?terms=breathless%2Bmahoney |accessdate=28 February 2020 |publisher=The Lancaster Intelligencer Journal |date=May 15, 1990}}</ref><ref name=\"Johnson\">{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Marilyn |title=Fashion detectives can track down 1940s duds |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/573197001/?terms=breathless%2Bmahoney |accessdate=28 February 2020 |publisher=Oceanside North County Times |date=May 30, 1990}}</ref> For example, the [[Los Angeles]] company L.A. Glo created a dress collection inspired by Breathless, with dress costs ranging from $70 to $180.<ref name=\"Herman\" /><ref name=\"Johnson\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Homan |first1=Becky |title=Not Left Breathless: Tracy's Fashion Statement Makes Barely a Whisper |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/141296236/?terms=breathless%2Bmahoney |accessdate=28 February 2020 |publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=July 12, 1990}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* {{cite book |last=Brunsdale |first=Mitzi M. |title=Icons of Mystery and Crime Detection: From Sleuths to Superheroes) |year=2010 |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]] |isbn=0313345309 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Guilbert |first=Georges-Claude |title=Madonna As Postmodern Myth: How One Star's Self-Construction Rewrites Sex, Gender, Hollywood and the American Dream |year=2002 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=0786414081 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Malburne-Wade |first=Meredith M. |title=The Encyclopedia of Sexism in American Films |year=2019 |editor1-last=Murgu\u00eda |editor1-first=Salvador Jimenez |editor2-last=Dymond |editor2-first=Erica Joan |editor3-last=Fennelly |editor3-first=Kristina |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |isbn=1538115514 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Roberts |first=Garyn G. |title=Dick Tracy and American Culture: Morality and Mythology, Text and Context |chapter=Dick Tracy (1990) |year=1993 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=0899508804 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thakur |first=Pradeep |title=Madonna: Unstoppable! |year=2010 |asin=B009AOICHU |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160422151836/http://www.imdb.com/character/ch0012366/ Breathless Mahoney] on [[IMDb]]\n{{Dick Tracy}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahoney, Breathless}}\n[[Category:Dick Tracy characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Film serial characters]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1945]]\n[[Category:Female characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Female film villains]]\n[[Category:Fictional singers]]\n\n\n{{film-char-stub}}\n{{comics-char-stub}}\n", "name_user": "NASCARfan0548", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"Femme fatale character in the American comic strip Dick Tracy\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breathless_Mahoney"}
{"title_page": "Hope Uzodinma", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Hope Uzodinma\n| image               = \n| caption             = Governor of Imo State\n| office2             = [[Senate of Nigeria|Senator of the Federal Republic]]\n| constituency2       = [[Imo State|Imo]] (west)\n| term_start2         = May 2011\n| term_end2           = May 2019\n| term_start          = 15 January 2020\n| predecessor2        = [[Osita Izunaso]]\n| office              = [[Governor of Imo State]]\n| predecessor         = [[Emeka Ihedioha]]\n| successor2          = [[Rochas Okorocha]]\n| birth_date          = 12 December 1958\n| birth_place         = [[Omuma town|Omuma]], [[Eastern Region, Nigeria]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>([[Omuma town|Omuma]], [[Imo State|Imo]], Nigeria)\n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = Nigerian\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress]]<br> (2018\u2013present)\n| alma_mater          = [[Washington University in St. Louis]]\n| occupation          = Politician\n| website             = {{URL|hopeuzodinma.com.ng}}\n| deputy              = [[Placid Njoku]]\n| spouse              = Chioma Uzodinma\n| otherparty          = [[National Party of Nigeria]]<br>(until 1983)<br>[[United Nigeria Congress Party]]<br>(1997\u20131998)<br>[[Alliance for Democracy (Nigeria)|Alliance for Democracy]]<br>(2002\u20132003)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democratic Party]]<br>(1999\u20132002; 2003\u20132018)\n}}\n'''Hope Odidika Uzodinma''' (born 12 December, 1958) is a [[Nigerian people|Nigerian]] politician who is currently the [[Governor]] of [[Imo State]], [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2020/01/15/breaking-hope-uzodinma-sworn-in-as-imo-state-governor/amp/|title=Hope Uzodinma Sworn in As Imo State Governor {{!}} Channels Television|website=www.channelstv.com|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref> On 14 January 2020, the Supreme Court in Nigeria declared Hope Uzodinma of the [[All Progressives Congress]] (APC) winner of the [[2019 Nigerian general election|2019 governorship poll]] in [[Imo State]] nullifying the election of incumbent [[Emeka Ihedioha]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-supreme-court-voids-ihediohas-election-declares-apc-uzodinma-imo-governor/|title=Supreme Court voids Ihedioha's election, declares APC Uzodinma Imo governor|last=Published|website=Punch Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nHope Uzodinma was born on 12 December 1958 in [[Omuma town|Omuma]]; his father Chief Michael Uzodinma held the [[Nigerian Chieftaincy|chieftaincy]] title of [[Igwe]] of [[Omuma town|Ozuh Omuma]] and his mother was Ezinne Rose Uzodinma (n\u00e9e Nneoha). He is a kinsman of the Okoro family of Etiti-Omuma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisdayonline.com/archive/2001/08/05/20010805cov02.html|title=Igbo Vote: Can These Men Deliver?|author1=Christian Ita|author2=Pius Anakali|date=5 August 2001|work=ThisDay|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041215062907/http://www.thisdayonline.com/archive/2001/08/05/20010805cov02.html|archivedate=15 December 2004|accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> \n\nHe holds a Diploma in Maritime Management Technology, and Higher Diploma in the same field, from the [[Federal University of Technology Owerri]]. He also has a [[bachelor's degree]] in International Studies and Diplomacy from [[Washington University in St. Louis]].\n\n=== Marriage and family ===\nUzodinma is a devout [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], and is married to Chioma Uzodinma with seven children.\n\n== Business career ==\nPrior to his entry into politics, Uzodinma was a businessman with vast business interests.\n\n==Political career==\n\n=== Party politics ===\nIn 1983, Hope Uzodinma began his political career as the Youth Leader of the [[National Party of Nigeria]] (NPN). In the 1990s, Uzodinma featured prominently as a member of the [[United Nigeria Congress Party]]. In 1999, following the transition from military rule to democracy, he became a member of the [[People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) serving on the pioneer [[PDP Board of Trustees|Board of Trustees]], National Caucus and NEC Member of the [[People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) between 1999-2017. \n\nUzodinma was a PDP chief in Imo State and friend of the Governor [[Achike Udenwa]] until late 2002. At that time he decided to run for Governor himself in the April 2003 elections, and decamped to the [[Alliance for Democracy (Nigeria)|Alliance for Democracy]] (AD), becoming their candidate for the Imo State gubernatorial election. He was unsuccessful, and in February 2004 was returned to the PDP.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://news.biafranigeriaworld.com/archive/2004/feb/26/049.html\n |date=26 February 2004\n |work=BNW News\n |accessdate=7 May 2011\n |title=Why Udenwa, Obi, shunned Uzodinma's readmission into PDP}}</ref> \n\nUzodinma was a competitor in the PDP primaries for Imo State Governor in December 2006, coming in second to Senator [[Ifeanyi Araraume]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.nigerianbestforum.com/blog/?p=30809\n |title=Hope Uzodinma adds one more year\n |author=ADAOBI NNEKA IFEBI\n |date=19 December 2009\n |work=NBF News\n |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> Uzodinma was appointed a member of the [[PDP Board of Trustees]]. He was among those who endorsed the bid by [[Ikedi Ohakim]] to run again for Imo Governor in 2011 after Ohakim had returned to the PDP.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://thenewsafrica.com/2010/11/15/imo-coalition-of-political-parties-endorses-ohakim-for-2011/\n |work=The News Africa\n |accessdate=7 May 2011\n |title=Imo Coalition Of Political Parties Endorses Ohakim For 2011\n |date=15 November 2010\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830232820/http://thenewsafrica.com/2010/11/15/imo-coalition-of-political-parties-endorses-ohakim-for-2011/\n |archivedate=30 August 2011\n \n}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011 senate election ===\nUzodinma won the PDP primary for the Imo West Senatorial race on 9 January 2011, gaining 2,147 votes, while the incumbent Senator [[Osita Izunaso]] came second with 891 votes. However, on 5 February 2011 a Federal High court declared that Izunaso was the candidate of the party for the senatorial seat since Uzodinma had not been cleared by the PDP's electoral panel headed by Orji Nwafor-Orizu.. The judge ordered the PDP to submit Izunaso's name to the [[Independent National Electoral Commission]] (INEC) as the candidate who had received the most votes among those qualified to run. A Court of Appeal issued a stay of execution on 17 March 2011 while the case was being decided, leaving Uzodinma free to campaign. On 5 April 2011 the Court of Appeal upheld 5 February high court judgement and declared that Uzodinma was not qualified to run and should not present himself as a candidate. Uzodinma appealed this decision at the Supreme Court.\n\nOn 9 April, 2011 elections, Uzodinma received 85,042 votes, ahead of former Imo Governor [[Achike Adenwa]] of the [[Action Congress of Nigeria]] (ACN) with 64,228 votes and Rajis Okpalan Benedicta of the [[All Progressives Grand Alliance]] with 57,110 votes. On 5 May, 2011 the Supreme Court overturned the earlier decisions and declared that Uzodinma was the valid candidate and therefore had been elected. The decision was influenced by the minutes of a 5 January 2011 meeting of the PDP's [[National Working Committee]] that was attached to the April appeal to the Supreme Court. The meeting had overruled Nwafor-Orizu's decision to disqualify Uzodinma and rejected the December 2010 petition, saying \"there was no evidence that Chief Hope Uzodinma has been convicted for murder, armed-robbery, obtaining money by false pretence and or for bankruptcy\".\n\n=== Senate (2011\u20132019) ===\nOn 29 May 2011, Uzodinma was sworn-in as a [[Senate of Nigeria|Senator]] of the [[Nigeria|Federal Republic of Nigeria]], representing [[Imo State]] (West Senatorial District). In 2018, he joined the ruling [[All Progressives Congress|All Progressive Congress]] (APC) and contested for [[Governor of Imo State]] in the [[2019 Nigerian general election|2019 general elections]]. \n\n=== 2019 governorship election ===\nIn March 2019, the [[Independent National Electoral Commission]] sitting in Imo announced the governorship election results of Imo State: [[Emeka Ihedioha]] of the PDP who won with 273,404 votes, [[Uche Nwosu]] of Action Alliance with 190,364 votes, [[Ifeanyi Ararume]] of the [[All Progressives Grand Alliance]] with 114,676 votes; and Udozinma in fourth place with 96,458 votes. Uzodinma later challenged the victory of Ihedioha up to the [[Supreme Court of Nigeria|Supreme Court]]. On 14 January 2020, the Supreme Court declared Uzodinma, the duly elected Governor of Imo State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2020/01/14/breaking-supreme-court-sacks-ihedioha-imo-governor-declares-hope-uzodinma-winner|title=BREAKING: Supreme Court Sacks Ihedioha As Imo Governor, Declares Hope Uzodinma Winner|last=siteadmin|date=14 January 2020|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/372652-why-supreme-court-sacked-ihedioha-declared-apcs-uzodinma-winner-in-imo.html|title=Why Supreme Court sacked Ihedioha, declared APC's Uzodinma winner|date=14 January 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> The court held that results from 388 polling units were wrongly excluded from votes ascribed to Uzodinma and the APC in Imo adding that the first appellant Uzodinma holds the majority of lawful votes cast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/ssouth-east/374161-download-supreme-court-judgement-that-gave-apcs-uzodinma-victory-in-imo.html|title=(Download) Supreme Court judgement that gave APC's Uzodinma victory in Imo|date=23 January 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Governor of Imo ===\nOn 15 January 2020, he was sworn-in as the [[Governor of Imo State]]. \n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Arrest allegation ===\nOn 11 November 2018, Uzodinma was allegedly arrested by a special investigation panel for the failure of one of his companies to execute a US$12 million contract for the dredging of Calabar channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/apcs-imo-governorship-candidate-hope-uzodinma-arrested-in-abuja/n2hd4l8|title=APC's Imo governorship candidate, Hope Uzodinma, arrested in Abuja|date=2018-11-12|website=Pulse Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Uzodinma later denied ever being arrested, saying it was an attempt to stop his campaign for governor.\n\n== Titles ==\nHe had the ceremonial title of Onwa-Netiri Oha of [[Omuma town|Omuma]] in [[Oru East|Oru]] local government of Imo State.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=Champion20110506>{{cite web\n |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201105060845.html\n |title=Imo West - Uzodinma Floors Izunaso\n |work=Daily Champion\n |author=Mebrim Uchechukwu\n |date=6 May 2011\n |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=leadership>{{cite web\n |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201105060324.html\n |title=Imo West - Uzodinma in, Izunaso Out\n |work=Leadership\n |author=George Agba\n |date=6 May 2011\n |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n}} \n{{Nigerian Senators of the 7th National Assembly}}\n{{Nigerian Senators of the 8th National Assembly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uzodinma, Hope}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate (Nigeria)]]\n[[Category:People from Imo State]]\n[[Category:Imo State politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Democratic Party members of the Senate (Nigeria)]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Hope Uzodinma\n| image               = \n| caption             = Governor of Imo State\n| office2             = [[Senate of Nigeria|Senator of the Federal Republic]]\n| constituency2       = [[Imo State|Imo]] (west)\n| term_start2         = May 2011\n| term_end2           = May 2019\n| term_start          = 15 January 2020\n| predecessor2        = [[Osita Izunaso]]\n| office              = [[Governor of Imo State]]\n| predecessor         = [[Emeka Ihedioha]]\n| successor2          = [[Rochas Okorocha]]\n| birth_date          = 12 December 1958\n| birth_place         = [[Omuma town|Omuma]], [[Eastern Region, Nigeria]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>([[Omuma town|Omuma]], [[Imo State|Imo]], Nigeria)\n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = Nigerian\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress]]<br> (2018\u2013present)\n| alma_mater          = [[Washington University in St. Louis]]\n| occupation          = Politician\n| website             = {{URL|hopeuzodinma.com.ng}}\n| deputy              = [[Placid Njoku]]\n| spouse              = Chioma Uzodinma\n| otherparty          = [[National Party of Nigeria]]<br>(until 1983)<br>[[United Nigeria Congress Party]]<br>(1997\u20131998)<br>[[Alliance for Democracy (Nigeria)|Alliance for Democracy]]<br>(2002\u20132003)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democratic Party]]<br>(1999\u20132002; 2003\u20132018)\n}}\n'''Hope Odidika Uzodinma''' (born 12 December, 1958) is a [[Nigerian people|Nigerian]] politician who is currently the [[Governor]] of [[Imo State]], [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2020/01/15/breaking-hope-uzodinma-sworn-in-as-imo-state-governor/amp/|title=Hope Uzodinma Sworn in As Imo State Governor {{!}} Channels Television|website=www.channelstv.com|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref> On 14 January 2020, the Supreme Court in Nigeria declared Hope Uzodinma of the [[All Progressives Congress]] (APC) winner of the [[2019 Nigerian general election|2019 governorship poll]] in [[Imo State]] nullifying the election of incumbent [[Emeka Ihedioha]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-supreme-court-voids-ihediohas-election-declares-apc-uzodinma-imo-governor/|title=Supreme Court voids Ihedioha's election, declares APC Uzodinma Imo governor|last=Published|website=Punch Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nHope Uzodinma was born on 12 December 1958 in [[Omuma town|Omuma]]; his father Chief Michael Uzodinma held the [[Nigerian Chieftaincy|chieftaincy]] title of [[Igwe]] of [[Omuma town|Ozuh Omuma]] and his mother was Ezinne Rose Uzodinma (n\u00e9e Nneoha). He is a kinsman of the Okoro family of Etiti-Omuma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisdayonline.com/archive/2001/08/05/20010805cov02.html|title=Igbo Vote: Can These Men Deliver?|author1=Christian Ita|author2=Pius Anakali|date=5 August 2001|work=ThisDay|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041215062907/http://www.thisdayonline.com/archive/2001/08/05/20010805cov02.html|archivedate=15 December 2004|accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> \n\nHe holds a Diploma in Maritime Management Technology, and Higher Diploma in the same field, from the [[Federal University of Technology Owerri]]. He also has a [[bachelor's degree]] in International Studies and Diplomacy from [[Washington University in St. Louis]].\n\n=== Marriage and family ===\nUzodinma is a devout [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], and is married to Chioma Uzodinma with seven children.\n\n== Business career ==\nPrior to his entry into politics, Uzodinma was a businessman with vast business interests. He cultivated clients, business associates and friends who have extended his interests beyond the normal scope of a businessman.\n\n==Political career==\n\n=== Party politics ===\nIn 1983, Hope Uzodinma began his political career as the Youth Leader of the [[National Party of Nigeria]] (NPN). In the 1990s, Uzodinma featured prominently as a member of the [[United Nigeria Congress Party]]. In 1999, following the transition from military rule to democracy, he became a member of the [[People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) serving on the pioneer [[PDP Board of Trustees|Board of Trustees]], National Caucus and NEC Member of the [[People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) between 1999-2017. \n\nUzodinma was a PDP chief in Imo State and friend of the Governor [[Achike Udenwa]] until late 2002. At that time he decided to run for Governor himself in the April 2003 elections, and decamped to the [[Alliance for Democracy (Nigeria)|Alliance for Democracy]] (AD), becoming their candidate for the Imo State gubernatorial election. He was unsuccessful, and in February 2004 was returned to the PDP.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://news.biafranigeriaworld.com/archive/2004/feb/26/049.html\n |date=26 February 2004\n |work=BNW News\n |accessdate=7 May 2011\n |title=Why Udenwa, Obi, shunned Uzodinma's readmission into PDP}}</ref> \n\nUzodinma was a competitor in the PDP primaries for Imo State Governor in December 2006, coming in second to Senator [[Ifeanyi Araraume]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.nigerianbestforum.com/blog/?p=30809\n |title=Hope Uzodinma adds one more year\n |author=ADAOBI NNEKA IFEBI\n |date=19 December 2009\n |work=NBF News\n |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> Uzodinma was appointed a member of the [[PDP Board of Trustees]]. He was among those who endorsed the bid by [[Ikedi Ohakim]] to run again for Imo Governor in 2011 after Ohakim had returned to the PDP.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://thenewsafrica.com/2010/11/15/imo-coalition-of-political-parties-endorses-ohakim-for-2011/\n |work=The News Africa\n |accessdate=7 May 2011\n |title=Imo Coalition Of Political Parties Endorses Ohakim For 2011\n |date=15 November 2010\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830232820/http://thenewsafrica.com/2010/11/15/imo-coalition-of-political-parties-endorses-ohakim-for-2011/\n |archivedate=30 August 2011\n \n}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011 senate election ===\nUzodinma won the PDP primary for the Imo West Senatorial race on 9 January 2011, gaining 2,147 votes, while the incumbent Senator [[Osita Izunaso]] came second with 891 votes. However, on 5 February 2011 a Federal High court declared that Izunaso was the candidate of the party for the senatorial seat since Uzodinma had not been cleared by the PDP's electoral panel headed by Orji Nwafor-Orizu.. The judge ordered the PDP to submit Izunaso's name to the [[Independent National Electoral Commission]] (INEC) as the candidate who had received the most votes among those qualified to run. A Court of Appeal issued a stay of execution on 17 March 2011 while the case was being decided, leaving Uzodinma free to campaign. On 5 April 2011 the Court of Appeal upheld 5 February high court judgement and declared that Uzodinma was not qualified to run and should not present himself as a candidate. Uzodinma appealed this decision at the Supreme Court.\n\nOn 9 April, 2011 elections, Uzodinma received 85,042 votes, ahead of former Imo Governor [[Achike Adenwa]] of the [[Action Congress of Nigeria]] (ACN) with 64,228 votes and Rajis Okpalan Benedicta of the [[All Progressives Grand Alliance]] with 57,110 votes. On 5 May, 2011 the Supreme Court overturned the earlier decisions and declared that Uzodinma was the valid candidate and therefore had been elected. The decision was influenced by the minutes of a 5 January 2011 meeting of the PDP's [[National Working Committee]] that was attached to the April appeal to the Supreme Court. The meeting had overruled Nwafor-Orizu's decision to disqualify Uzodinma and rejected the December 2010 petition, saying \"there was no evidence that Chief Hope Uzodinma has been convicted for murder, armed-robbery, obtaining money by false pretence and or for bankruptcy\".\n\n=== Senate (2011\u20132019) ===\nOn 29 May 2011, Uzodinma was sworn-in as a [[Senate of Nigeria|Senator]] of the [[Nigeria|Federal Republic of Nigeria]], representing [[Imo State]] (West Senatorial District). In 2018, he joined the ruling [[All Progressives Congress|All Progressive Congress]] (APC) and contested for [[Governor of Imo State]] in the [[2019 Nigerian general election|2019 general elections]]. \n\n=== 2019 governorship election ===\nIn March 2019, the [[Independent National Electoral Commission]] sitting in Imo announced the governorship election results of Imo State: [[Emeka Ihedioha]] of the PDP who won with 273,404 votes, [[Uche Nwosu]] of Action Alliance with 190,364 votes, [[Ifeanyi Ararume]] of the [[All Progressives Grand Alliance]] with 114,676 votes; and Udozinma in fourth place with 96,458 votes. Uzodinma later challenged the victory of Ihedioha up to the [[Supreme Court of Nigeria|Supreme Court]]. On 14 January 2020, the Supreme Court declared Uzodinma, the duly elected Governor of Imo State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2020/01/14/breaking-supreme-court-sacks-ihedioha-imo-governor-declares-hope-uzodinma-winner|title=BREAKING: Supreme Court Sacks Ihedioha As Imo Governor, Declares Hope Uzodinma Winner|last=siteadmin|date=14 January 2020|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/372652-why-supreme-court-sacked-ihedioha-declared-apcs-uzodinma-winner-in-imo.html|title=Why Supreme Court sacked Ihedioha, declared APC's Uzodinma winner|date=14 January 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> The court held that results from 388 polling units were wrongly excluded from votes ascribed to Uzodinma and the APC in Imo adding that the first appellant Uzodinma holds the majority of lawful votes cast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/ssouth-east/374161-download-supreme-court-judgement-that-gave-apcs-uzodinma-victory-in-imo.html|title=(Download) Supreme Court judgement that gave APC's Uzodinma victory in Imo|date=23 January 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Governor of Imo ===\nOn 15 January 2020, he was sworn-in as the [[Governor of Imo State]]. \n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Arrest allegation ===\nOn 11 November 2018, Uzodinma was allegedly arrested by a special investigation panel for the failure of one of his companies to execute a US$12 million contract for the dredging of Calabar channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/apcs-imo-governorship-candidate-hope-uzodinma-arrested-in-abuja/n2hd4l8|title=APC's Imo governorship candidate, Hope Uzodinma, arrested in Abuja|date=2018-11-12|website=Pulse Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Uzodinma later denied ever being arrested, saying it was an attempt to stop his campaign for governor.\n\n== Titles ==\nHe had the ceremonial title of Onwa-Netiri Oha of [[Omuma town|Omuma]] in [[Oru East|Oru]] local government of Imo State.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=Champion20110506>{{cite web\n |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201105060845.html\n |title=Imo West - Uzodinma Floors Izunaso\n |work=Daily Champion\n |author=Mebrim Uchechukwu\n |date=6 May 2011\n |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=leadership>{{cite web\n |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201105060324.html\n |title=Imo West - Uzodinma in, Izunaso Out\n |work=Leadership\n |author=George Agba\n |date=6 May 2011\n |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n}} \n{{Nigerian Senators of the 7th National Assembly}}\n{{Nigerian Senators of the 8th National Assembly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uzodinma, Hope}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate (Nigeria)]]\n[[Category:People from Imo State]]\n[[Category:Imo State politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Democratic Party members of the Senate (Nigeria)]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n", "name_user": "Zerzuran", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBusiness career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hope_Uzodinma"}
{"title_page": "1890 Wimbledon Championships", "text_new": "{{Infobox tennis tournament year|1890|Wimbledon Championships|\n| date     = 30 June - 7 July (singles)<br />21 \u2013 23 July (doubles)\n| edition  = 14th\n| location = Worple Road<br>[[SW19]], [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]],<br>London, United Kingdom\n| venue    = [[All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club|All England Lawn Tennis Club]]\n| surface  = [[Grass court|Grass]]\n| category = [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]]\n| champms  = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Willoughby Hamilton]]\n| champws  = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Lena Rice]]\n| champmd  = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Joshua Pim]] / {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Stoker]]\n}}\nThe '''1890 Wimbledon Championships''' was a combined men's and women's [[tennis]] tournament that took place on the outdoor grass courts at the [[All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club|All England Lawn Tennis Club]] in [[Wimbledon, London]], [[United Kingdom]]. The tournament ran from 30 June until 7 July.<ref name=\"Little\">2010 Wimbledon Compendium, by Alan Little (The All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club, Wimbledon, London)</ref> It was the 14th staging of the [[Wimbledon Championships]], and the first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tennis event of 1890.<ref name=\"Tingay\" /> Bonham Carter Evelegh took over as referee from [[Julian Marshall]].<ref name=\"Tingay\">100 Years of Wimbledon by Lance Tingay (Guinness Superlatives Ltd. 1977)</ref> The rule for [[Glossary of tennis#change-over|change-over]]s was altered to after every odd game.<ref name=\"Tingay\" /> There were 30 competitors for the men's singles and only four competitors for the women's singles, the smallest entry ever for any competition at Wimbledon.<ref name=\"Tingay\" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Wimbledon : The Official History of the Championships|year=2001|publisher=CollinsWillow|location=London|isbn=0007117078|author=John Barrett|page=30}}</ref>  The final of the women's singles competition, which started on 2 July, was played on 5 July, while the men's singles final was played on 7 July and the men's doubles were played on 21\u201323 July.<ref name=\"Little\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Lawn Tennis|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gP1UAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RJMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5330%2C1892384|newspaper=The Sydney Mail|date=Aug 16, 1890}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lawn Tennis|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18900705/024/0003|work=Morning Post|publisher=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|date=5 July 1890|page=3|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Finals==\n\n===Gentlemen's Singles===\n{{main|1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles}}\n{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Willoughby Hamilton]] defeated {{flagicon|GBR}} [[William Renshaw]], 6\u20138, 6\u20132, 3\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20131 <ref name=\"menss\">{{cite web|title=Gentlemen's Singles Finals 1877-2016|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/gentlemenssingles.html|website=wimbledon.com|publisher=[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ladies' Singles===\n{{main|1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Ladies' Singles}}\n{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Lena Rice]] defeated {{flagicon|GBR}} [[May Jacks]], 6\u20134, 6\u20131 <ref name=\"womenss\">{{cite web|title=Ladies' Singles Finals 1884-2016|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/ladiessingles.html|website=wimbledon.com|publisher=[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Gentlemen's Doubles===\n{{Main|1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles}}\n{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Joshua Pim]] / {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Stoker]] defeated {{flagicon|GBR}} [[George Hillyard]] / {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Lewis (tennis)|Ernest Lewis]], 6\u20130, 7\u20135, 6\u20134 <ref name=\"mensd\">{{cite web|title=Gentlemen's Doubles Finals 1884-2016|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/gentlemensdoubles.html|website=wimbledon.com|publisher=[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wimbledon.com/index.html Official Wimbledon Championships website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before=[[1889 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1889 U.S. National Championships]]| title=[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] | years= | after=[[1890 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1890 U.S. National Championships]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Wimbledon championships}}\n\n[[Category:1890 Wimbledon Championships| ]]\n[[Category:1890 in English sport|Wimbledon Championships]]\n[[Category:1890 in London|Wimbledon Championships]]\n[[Category:1890 in tennis|Wimbledon Championships]]\n[[Category:June 1890 sports events]]\n[[Category:July 1890 sports events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox tennis tournament year|1890|Wimbledon Championships|\n| date     = 30 June - 7 July (singles)<br />21 \u2013 23 July (doubles)\n| edition  = 14th\n| location = Worple Road<br>[[SW19]], [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]],<br>London, United Kingdom\n| venue    = [[All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club|All England Lawn Tennis Club]]\n| surface  = [[Grass court|Grass]]\n| category = [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]]\n| champms  = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Willoughby Hamilton]]\n| champws  = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Lena Rice]]\n| champmd  = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Joshua Pim]] / {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Stoker]]\n}}\nThe '''1890 Wimbledon Championships''' was a combined men's and women's [[tennis]] tournament that took place on the outdoor grass courts at the [[All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club|All England Lawn Tennis Club]] in [[Wimbledon, London]], [[United Kingdom]]. The tournament ran from 30 June until 7 July.<ref name=\"Little\">2010 Wimbledon Compendium, by Alan Little (The All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club, Wimbledon, London)</ref> It was the 14th staging of the [[Wimbledon Championships]], and the first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tennis event of 1890.<ref name=\"Tingay\" /> Bonham Carter Evelegh took over as referee from [[Julian Marshall]].<ref name=\"Tingay\">100 Years of Wimbledon by Lance Tingay (Guinness Superlatives Ltd. 1977)</ref> The rule for [[Glossary of tennis#change-over|change-over]]s was altered to after every odd game.<ref name=\"Tingay\" /> There were 30 competitors for the men's singles and only four competitors for the women's singles, the smallest entry ever for any competition at Wimbledon.<ref name=\"Tingay\" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Wimbledon : The Official History of the Championships|year=2001|publisher=CollinsWillow|location=London|isbn=0007117078|author=John Barrett|page=30}}</ref>  The final of the women's singles competition, which started on 2 July, was played on 5 July, while the men's singles final was played on 7 July and the men's doubles were played on 21\u201323 July.<ref name=\"Little\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Lawn Tennis|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gP1UAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RJMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5330%2C1892384|newspaper=The Sydney Mail|date=Aug 16, 1890}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lawn Tennis|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18900705/024/0003|work=Morning Post|publisher=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|date=5 July 1890|page=3|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Finals==\n\n===Gentlemen's Singles===\n{{main|1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles}}\n{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Willoughby Hamilton]] defeated {{flagicon|GBR}} [[William Renshaw]], 6\u20138, 6\u20132, 3\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20131 <ref name=\"menss\">{{cite web|title=Gentlemen's Singles Finals 1877-2016|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/gentlemenssingles.html|website=wimbledon.com|publisher=[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ladies' Singles===\n{{main|1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Ladies' Singles}}\n{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Lena Rice]] defeated {{flagicon|GBR}} [[May Jacks]], 6\u20134, 6\u20131 <ref name=\"womenss\">{{cite web|title=Ladies' Singles Finals 1884-2016|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/ladiessingles.html|website=wimbledon.com|publisher=[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Gentlemen's Doubles===\n{{Main|1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles}}\n{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Joshua Pim]] / {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Stoker]] defeated {{flagicon|GBR}} [[George Hillyard]] / {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Lewis]], 6\u20130, 7\u20135, 6\u20134 <ref name=\"mensd\">{{cite web|title=Gentlemen's Doubles Finals 1884-2016|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/gentlemensdoubles.html|website=wimbledon.com|publisher=[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wimbledon.com/index.html Official Wimbledon Championships website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before=[[1889 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1889 U.S. National Championships]]| title=[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] | years= | after=[[1890 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1890 U.S. National Championships]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Wimbledon championships}}\n\n[[Category:1890 Wimbledon Championships| ]]\n[[Category:1890 in English sport|Wimbledon Championships]]\n[[Category:1890 in London|Wimbledon Championships]]\n[[Category:1890 in tennis|Wimbledon Championships]]\n[[Category:June 1890 sports events]]\n[[Category:July 1890 sports events]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - fix links -Ernest Lewis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1890_Wimbledon_Championships"}
{"title_page": "Sidney Maynard Smith", "text_new": "'''Sidney Maynard Smith''' [[Companion of The Most Honourable Order of the Bath|CB]]  [[Knight of Grace of the Order of St John|KStJ]] [[Fellowship of the Royal College of Surgeons|FRCS]] (20 September 1875 \u2013 18 March 1928) was a British [[surgeon]] and [[freemason]].<ref>[[Plarr's Lives of the Fellows]] Online http://livesonline.rcseng.ac.uk/biogs/E003604b.htm</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmc = 2455606 | pmid=20773785 | volume=1 | issue=3507 | title=SIDNEY MAYNARD SMITH, C.B., F.R.C.S |date=March 1928 | journal=Br Med J | pages=526\u20137 | doi=10.1136/bmj.1.3507.526}}</ref><ref>Epsom College Archive: Biographies of Old Epsomiams: Smith, Sidney Maynard [http://archive.epsomcollege.org.uk/1851-1889/OE_Biographies/Smith1889.pdf]</ref><ref>'SMITH, Maynard', Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132008; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2007 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U203101 accessed 5 May 2013]</ref>\n\nSmith was the son of W.H. Smith, a civil engineer attached to the [[Admiralty]] (not to be confused with [[William H. Smith (1825-1891)|the W.H.Smith]] who was a [[First Lord of the Admiralty]]).  He was educated at [[Epsom College]] and [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]], as was his older brother Percy Montague Smith (1871-1961), who was also a doctor and became FRCS.<ref name=\"Percy obituary\">{{cite journal| pmc=1969830 | page=835 | volume=2 | issue=5255 | journal=Br Med J | title=Obituary: P. MONTAGUE SMITH, M.D., F.R.C.S | doi=10.1136/bmj.2.5255.835-b}}</ref>\n\nHe served during the [[Boer War]] as a surgeon.  For service during the [[First World War]], he served in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] and was awarded the [[Order of the Bath|CB]] by Britain and the [[croix de guerre]] by France; he was thrice [[mentioned in dispatches]].  He was appointed consulting surgeon to the [[British Fifth Army]] in 1916, and later consulting surgeon to the [[British Second Army]].  For his service during the war, he was appointed Knight of Grace of the Order of St John on 1 December 1916<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29848 |date=5 December 1916 |page=11839 }}</ref> and Companion of The Order of the Bath (Military Division) on 1 January 1918<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30450 |date=1 January 1918 |page=2 |supp=y |nolink=yes }}</ref> (recommended 23 September 1917).<ref>http://www.awm.gov.au/research/people/honours_and_awards/person.asp?p=440488</ref>\n\nHe became Senior Surgeon at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]] in 1922 following the retirement of [[Ernest Lane (surgeon)|Ernest Lane]].\n\nAs a [[freemason]] he was Grand Deacon of the [[Grand Lodge of England]].\n\nIn 1917, he married Isabel Mary Pitman, daughter of [[Frederick I. Pitman]].  They had a daughter Isabel Valentine Maynard Smith (born 1919), and a son, the biologist [[John Maynard Smith]] (1920-2004).  In later life John Maynard Smith described his father as being \"a poor boy made good\" who married into \"[[landed gentry]]\", and recalled of their relationship prior to Sidney's death when John was eight years old \"I hardly knew him; we saw him sort of [[Sunday lunch]] - literally\".<ref name=\"Web of Stories\">[http://www.webofstories.com/play/4624 Interview of [[John Maynard Smith]] by [[Richard Dawkins]]: \"Early childhood and a passion for natural history\" [[Web of Stories]] April 1997]</ref>  He and his family lived at No. 49 [[Wimpole Street]] in [[Westminster]]<ref>Ladies' Who's Who - Page 598 books.google.com/books?id=zu4WAQAAIAAJ</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maynard Smith, Sidney}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:British surgeons]]\n[[Category:People educated at Epsom College]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Surgeons]]\n[[Category:Knights of Grace of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Freemasons of the United Grand Lodge of England]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Medical Corps officers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sidney Maynard Smith''' [[Companion of The Most Honourable Order of the Bath|CB]]  [[Knight of Grace of the Order of St John|KStJ]] [[Fellowship of the Royal College of Surgeons|FRCS]] (20 September 1875 \u2013 18 March 1928) was a British [[surgeon]] and [[freemason]].<ref>[[Plarr's Lives of the Fellows]] Online http://livesonline.rcseng.ac.uk/biogs/E003604b.htm</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmc = 2455606 | pmid=20773785 | volume=1 | issue=3507 | title=SIDNEY MAYNARD SMITH, C.B., F.R.C.S |date=March 1928 | journal=Br Med J | pages=526\u20137 | doi=10.1136/bmj.1.3507.526}}</ref><ref>Epsom College Archive: Biographies of Old Epsomiams: Smith, Sidney Maynard [http://archive.epsomcollege.org.uk/1851-1889/OE_Biographies/Smith1889.pdf]</ref><ref>'SMITH, Maynard', Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132008; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2007 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U203101 accessed 5 May 2013]</ref>\n\nSmith was the son of W.H. Smith, a civil engineer attached to the [[Admiralty]] (not to be confused with [[William H. Smith (1825-1891)|the W.H.Smith]] who was a [[First Lord of the Admiralty]]).  He was educated at [[Epsom College]] and [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]], as was his older brother Percy Montague Smith (1871-1961), who was also a doctor and became FRCS.<ref name=\"Percy obituary\">{{cite journal| pmc=1969830 | page=835 | volume=2 | issue=5255 | journal=Br Med J | title=Obituary: P. MONTAGUE SMITH, M.D., F.R.C.S | doi=10.1136/bmj.2.5255.835-b}}</ref>\n\nHe served during the [[Boer War]] as a surgeon.  For service during the [[First World War]], he served in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] and was awarded the [[Order of the Bath|CB]] by Britain and the [[croix de guerre]] by France; he was thrice [[mentioned in dispatches]].  He was appointed consulting surgeon to the [[British Fifth Army]] in 1916, and later consulting surgeon to the [[British Second Army]].  For his service during the war, he was appointed Knight of Grace of the Order of St John on 1 December 1916<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29848 |date=5 December 1916 |page=11839 }}</ref> and Companion of The Order of the Bath (Military Division) on 1 January 1918<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30450 |date=1 January 1918 |page=2 |supp=y |nolink=yes }}</ref> (recommended 23 September 1917).<ref>http://www.awm.gov.au/research/people/honours_and_awards/person.asp?p=440488</ref>\n\nHe became Senior Surgeon at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]] in 1922 following the retirement of [[Ernest Lane]].\n\nAs a [[freemason]] he was Grand Deacon of the [[Grand Lodge of England]].\n\nIn 1917, he married Isabel Mary Pitman, daughter of [[Frederick I. Pitman]].  They had a daughter Isabel Valentine Maynard Smith (born 1919), and a son, the biologist [[John Maynard Smith]] (1920-2004).  In later life John Maynard Smith described his father as being \"a poor boy made good\" who married into \"[[landed gentry]]\", and recalled of their relationship prior to Sidney's death when John was eight years old \"I hardly knew him; we saw him sort of [[Sunday lunch]] - literally\".<ref name=\"Web of Stories\">[http://www.webofstories.com/play/4624 Interview of [[John Maynard Smith]] by [[Richard Dawkins]]: \"Early childhood and a passion for natural history\" [[Web of Stories]] April 1997]</ref>  He and his family lived at No. 49 [[Wimpole Street]] in [[Westminster]]<ref>Ladies' Who's Who - Page 598 books.google.com/books?id=zu4WAQAAIAAJ</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maynard Smith, Sidney}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:British surgeons]]\n[[Category:People educated at Epsom College]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Surgeons]]\n[[Category:Knights of Grace of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Freemasons of the United Grand Lodge of England]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Medical Corps officers]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Ernest Lane", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidney_Maynard_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Ida Mann", "text_new": "{{one source|date=November 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = Professor [[Dame]]\n| name              = Ida Caroline Mann<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellowship of the Royal College of Surgeons|FRCS]]</small>\n| image             = Ida Caroline Mann.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = 6 February 1893\n| birth_place       = [[West Hampstead]], London, England, UK\n| death_date        = 18 November 1983 (aged 90)\n| death_place       = [[Perth, Western Australia]]\n| fields            = [[Ophthalmology]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Oxford]]\n| alma_mater        = London School of Medicine for Women}}\n\n'''Professor Dame Ida Caroline Mann, Mrs Gye''', [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellowship of the Royal College of Surgeons|FRCS]] (6 February 1893, [[West Hampstead]], London{{spaced ndash}} 18 November 1983, [[Perth, Western Australia]]) was \"a distinguished ophthalmologist ... equally well known for her pioneering research work on embryology and development of the eye, and on the influences of genetic and social factors on the incidence and severity of eye disease throughout the world\".<ref name=ODNB>J. M. Tiffany, 'Mann, Dame Ida Caroline (1893\u20131983)', ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (OUP, 2004)</ref> Only six other women were Fellows at this time.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 68</ref>\n\n==Education==\nIda Caroline Mann was educated at Wycombe House School, Hampstead, London.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 27</ref> She passed the Civil Service Girl Clerk's examination and took a job at the Post Office Savings Bank.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 46</ref>\n\nDespite opposition from her father, she applied to study medicine at the [[London School of Medicine for Women]], the only medical school which was open to women at that time. She passed the matriculation examination in 1914, one of only eight women out of hundreds of passes.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 48\u201349</ref> She completed her studies, 'with no trouble and intense delight', and qualified Bachelor of Medicine and Bachelor of Surgery (MB, BS) in 1920.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 64</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter qualification she had no clear idea about specialising and applied for all available positions as a houseman (a junior role for newly qualified doctors). She was appointed as the Ophthalmic House Surgeon at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]], under Leslie Paton and Frank Juler.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 66</ref> Thus began a lifelong passion for ophthalmic research and practice. During her medical studies she had developed an interest in embryology, working alongside Professor J. E. S. Frazer.\n\nNow she combined this interest with ophthalmology and wrote her thesis on the embryology of the human eye, for which she was awarded her D.Sc. in 1924.<ref name=Chase-67>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 67</ref> To further her career she qualified in general surgery, becoming a [[Fellow of the Royal College of Surgeons]] in 1924.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\nMann was ambitious and determined to reach the top in her chosen field. To her this meant securing an honorary staff post at [[Moorfields Eye Hospital]], London, and running her own private practice at [[Harley Street]], London.<ref name=Chase-67/> She had achieved both by 1927.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\nHer stepping stones had been the following posts: Junior Clinical Assistant at Moorfields (1921); staff appointment at the [[Elizabeth Garrett Anderson Hospital for Women]] (1922); Senior Clinical Assistant to Mr A. C. Hudson at Moorfields (1922); Pathologist and Assistant Surgeon to Mr [[Ernest Lane (surgeon)|Ernest Lane]] at the Central London Ophthalmic Hospital (1925); staff appointment at the Central London Eye Hospital (1925).{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Second World War==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=July 2017}}\nAt the outbreak of war, Moorfields Eye Hospital was commandeered as a first aid post and the staff were dispersed. The premises in which Mann conducted her private practice were also closed down by the landlord. She found new premises for her own practice and then set about re-siting Moorfields. She found hospital premises in Edgware (10 miles from central London), belonging to the Priory of the Holy Sepulchre, secured the lease, moved the nursing staff there and saw the gradual return of the surgical staff.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 114\u201315</ref>\n\nThere was still a need for a central London site to treat ophthalmic emergencies, and by a mixture of bravado and sheer energy, she managed to re-occupy part of the old Moorfields Hospital on City Road, which remained operational throughout the war despite being bombed. In 1940 she undertook some personal research on the treatment of mustard gas burns of the eye, using laboratories belonging to the Imperial Cancer Research Fund at Mill Hill. It was here she met her future husband, Professor William Gye, the fund's director.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nWhen the results of her private research became known, she was put in charge of one of the research teams of the Chemical Defence Research Department under the Ministry of Supply. Working with her friend, Davidine Pullinger, and the biochemist, Antoinette Pirie, she worked out the entire pathology of mustard gas keratitis, which afflicted soldiers from the First World War some ten to fifteen years after they had survived a mustard gas attack. Although the team did not find a cure, they were able to alleviate symptoms through the use of contact lenses.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 117\u201318.</ref>\n\n==Oxford==\nDuring the war, honorary staff were not allowed to resign from their posts at civilian hospitals. Therefore, when Mann applied for, and was appointed to, the post of Margaret Ogilvy Reader in Ophthalmology at the [[University of Oxford]] in 1941, she was obliged to combine this research and teaching post with her work at Moorfields in London, her work on the Chemical Defence Research team and her work as a private consultant in London and Oxford.\n\nDuring her tenure at Oxford, among other achievements, she oversaw the building of the [[Nuffield College|Nuffield Laboratory of Ophthalmology]], restarted the diploma courses for post-graduates, inaugurated the Orthoptic School and re-instituted the [[Oxford Ophthalmological Congress]]. In her own words, she had 'cleared the Augean stable' in nine months.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 127\u201328</ref>\n\nHer efforts were recognised by the university in 1945 when she was given a personal professorship: the first woman to receive one at Oxford. She was Titular Professor there from January 1945 until 30 September 1947. Mann was also a Fellow of [[St Hugh's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/oxford-people/women-at-oxford|title=Women at Oxford|accessdate=1 February 2019|work=University of Oxford}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nMann became acquainted with [[William Ewart Gye]], known as Bill Gye, who was Director of the Imperial Cancer Research Fund at Mill Hill, and his wife, [[Elsa Gye|Elsa]], during the war. After Elsa death from cancer, Mann and Gye married in December 1944.<ref>{{cite journal|title=W. E. Gye. M.D., F.R.C.P., F.R.S,|journal=British Medical Journal|date=25 October 1952|volume=2|issue=4790|pages=945\u2013946|pmc=2021835|pmid=12978397}}</ref> Mann became stepmother to her husband's three sons from his first marriage. She did not change her name on marriage, as the complications arising from having two Professor Gyes in the same household were easily foreseen.\n\n==Australia==\nMann had first visited Australia in 1939 as the British Medical Association's representative at the 1st Annual General Meeting of the Ophthalmological Society of Australia (B.M.A.). She flew there in an Imperial Airways Flying Boat, which took a week to fly at low altitude from Southampton to Melbourne. She gave a number of papers and made the return journey \"with the feeling that the gloom of Europe would soon descend, and that this brilliant, sunny and friendly land would be blotted from my memory\" (Mann: ''The Chase'').<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 108\u201311</ref> In 1949 she and her husband set off for Perth and Melbourne on an autumn cruise.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 138</ref>\n\nThe introduction of the [[National Health Service]] in Britain had drastically changed Mann's work and she was dissatisfied with the impact on ophthalmology. Perhaps more pressingly her husband had retired from Mill Hill and was suffering from ill-health which was exacerbated by the English winters. They were immediately smitten with Perth. Mann purchased a bungalow in Dalkeith, resigned from Moorfields, and arranged for all their belongings to be shipped to Australia.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 140\u201341</ref> Here they conducted experiments on cancer viruses using in-bred strains of mice to ensure consistency.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 141\u201342</ref> She started a private practice as an ophthalmologist, which was always her insurance against economic uncertainty.<ref name=Chase-143>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 143</ref>\n\n==Trachoma research==\nBill died in 1952, leaving her bereft, 'I was unhinged; so tired that I was almost insane'.<ref name=Chase-143/> She regained her balance by working and traveling. Shortly after his death she took an assignment reporting on the incidence of eye disease for the Western Australia Public Health Department. This assignment extended to four years and provided incontrovertible proof of endemic trachoma among the indigenous population.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986)<!-- page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nShe traveled extensively throughout Australia and Oceania studying the incidence of eye disease in different races and cultures, with particular reference to the Aboriginal people. This research produced the classic work, ''Culture, Race, Climate and Eye Disease'' (1966).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/blue-plaques/ida-mann/|title=Mann, Dame Ida (1893-1983)|accessdate=1 February 2019|work=english-heritage.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nMann published extensively in the area of eye anatomy and eye disease, publishing many scientific articles and several books. She also wrote on her travels and findings relating to [[trachoma]], published under her married name '''Ida Gye''' or a pseudonym, '''Caroline Gye'''. These were ''China 13'' and ''The Cockney and the Crocodile''.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Honors==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\n*She was appointed CBE in 1950 and DBE in 1980 for services to the welfare of Aboriginal people. \n*She was inducted into the Ophthalmology Hall of Fame in 2007. \n*She received an honorary Doctor of Science from Murdoch University (Perth, Western Australia) in 1983.\n\n==Death==\nDame Ida Mann died at her home in Perth in 1983, aged 90.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Publications==\n* Ida Mann, ''The Development of the Human Eye'' (Cambridge, 1928)\n* Ida Mann, ''Developmental Abnormalities of the Eye'' (Cambridge, 1937)\n* Ida Mann and Antoinette Pirie, ''The Science of Seeing'' (Harmondsworth, 1946)\n* Ida Mann, ''Culture, Race, Climate and Eye Disease'' (Illinois, 1966)\n* Caroline Gye, ''The Cockney and the Crocodile'' (London, 1962)\n* Caroline Gye, ''China 13'' (London, 1964)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Mann, Ida, ''The Chase: an autobiography'', edited by Ros Golding (Fremantle Arts Centre Press, 1986)\n* Radi, Heather (editor), ''200 Australian Women'', Women's Press: Sydney, 1988.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070620185928/http://www.oxfordeyeupdates.com/page/page/2123438.htm Profile], oxfordeyeupdates.com; accessed 1 April 2014\n*[http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/IMP0041b.htm Profile], womenaustralia.info; accessed 1 April 2014 \n*[http://www.snof.org/maladies/embryohist.html Profile], snof.org; accessed 1 April 2014\n*[http://www.bodley.ox.ac.uk/dept/scwmss/wmss/online/modern/mann-ida/mann-ida.html Catalogue of papers of Ida Mann held at the Bodleian Library], University of Oxford website; accessed 1 April 2014\n*[http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0690b.htm Mann, Ida Caroline (1893\u20131983)] in ''The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mann, Ida}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Australia]]\n[[Category:British humanitarians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British writers]]\n[[Category:Australian Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:People from West Hampstead]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Surgeons]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Medicine for Women]]\n[[Category:Women ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:Vision scientists]]\n[[Category:Female vision scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n", "text_old": "{{one source|date=November 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = Professor [[Dame]]\n| name              = Ida Caroline Mann<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellowship of the Royal College of Surgeons|FRCS]]</small>\n| image             = Ida Caroline Mann.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = 6 February 1893\n| birth_place       = [[West Hampstead]], London, England, UK\n| death_date        = 18 November 1983 (aged 90)\n| death_place       = [[Perth, Western Australia]]\n| fields            = [[Ophthalmology]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Oxford]]\n| alma_mater        = London School of Medicine for Women}}\n\n'''Professor Dame Ida Caroline Mann, Mrs Gye''', [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellowship of the Royal College of Surgeons|FRCS]] (6 February 1893, [[West Hampstead]], London{{spaced ndash}} 18 November 1983, [[Perth, Western Australia]]) was \"a distinguished ophthalmologist ... equally well known for her pioneering research work on embryology and development of the eye, and on the influences of genetic and social factors on the incidence and severity of eye disease throughout the world\".<ref name=ODNB>J. M. Tiffany, 'Mann, Dame Ida Caroline (1893\u20131983)', ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (OUP, 2004)</ref> Only six other women were Fellows at this time.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 68</ref>\n\n==Education==\nIda Caroline Mann was educated at Wycombe House School, Hampstead, London.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 27</ref> She passed the Civil Service Girl Clerk's examination and took a job at the Post Office Savings Bank.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 46</ref>\n\nDespite opposition from her father, she applied to study medicine at the [[London School of Medicine for Women]], the only medical school which was open to women at that time. She passed the matriculation examination in 1914, one of only eight women out of hundreds of passes.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 48\u201349</ref> She completed her studies, 'with no trouble and intense delight', and qualified Bachelor of Medicine and Bachelor of Surgery (MB, BS) in 1920.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 64</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter qualification she had no clear idea about specialising and applied for all available positions as a houseman (a junior role for newly qualified doctors). She was appointed as the Ophthalmic House Surgeon at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]], under Leslie Paton and Frank Juler.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 66</ref> Thus began a lifelong passion for ophthalmic research and practice. During her medical studies she had developed an interest in embryology, working alongside Professor J. E. S. Frazer.\n\nNow she combined this interest with ophthalmology and wrote her thesis on the embryology of the human eye, for which she was awarded her D.Sc. in 1924.<ref name=Chase-67>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 67</ref> To further her career she qualified in general surgery, becoming a [[Fellow of the Royal College of Surgeons]] in 1924.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\nMann was ambitious and determined to reach the top in her chosen field. To her this meant securing an honorary staff post at [[Moorfields Eye Hospital]], London, and running her own private practice at [[Harley Street]], London.<ref name=Chase-67/> She had achieved both by 1927.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\nHer stepping stones had been the following posts: Junior Clinical Assistant at Moorfields (1921); staff appointment at the [[Elizabeth Garrett Anderson Hospital for Women]] (1922); Senior Clinical Assistant to Mr A. C. Hudson at Moorfields (1922); Pathologist and Assistant Surgeon to Mr [[Ernest Lane]] at the Central London Ophthalmic Hospital (1925); staff appointment at the Central London Eye Hospital (1925).{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Second World War==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=July 2017}}\nAt the outbreak of war, Moorfields Eye Hospital was commandeered as a first aid post and the staff were dispersed. The premises in which Mann conducted her private practice were also closed down by the landlord. She found new premises for her own practice and then set about re-siting Moorfields. She found hospital premises in Edgware (10 miles from central London), belonging to the Priory of the Holy Sepulchre, secured the lease, moved the nursing staff there and saw the gradual return of the surgical staff.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 114\u201315</ref>\n\nThere was still a need for a central London site to treat ophthalmic emergencies, and by a mixture of bravado and sheer energy, she managed to re-occupy part of the old Moorfields Hospital on City Road, which remained operational throughout the war despite being bombed. In 1940 she undertook some personal research on the treatment of mustard gas burns of the eye, using laboratories belonging to the Imperial Cancer Research Fund at Mill Hill. It was here she met her future husband, Professor William Gye, the fund's director.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nWhen the results of her private research became known, she was put in charge of one of the research teams of the Chemical Defence Research Department under the Ministry of Supply. Working with her friend, Davidine Pullinger, and the biochemist, Antoinette Pirie, she worked out the entire pathology of mustard gas keratitis, which afflicted soldiers from the First World War some ten to fifteen years after they had survived a mustard gas attack. Although the team did not find a cure, they were able to alleviate symptoms through the use of contact lenses.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 117\u201318.</ref>\n\n==Oxford==\nDuring the war, honorary staff were not allowed to resign from their posts at civilian hospitals. Therefore, when Mann applied for, and was appointed to, the post of Margaret Ogilvy Reader in Ophthalmology at the [[University of Oxford]] in 1941, she was obliged to combine this research and teaching post with her work at Moorfields in London, her work on the Chemical Defence Research team and her work as a private consultant in London and Oxford.\n\nDuring her tenure at Oxford, among other achievements, she oversaw the building of the [[Nuffield College|Nuffield Laboratory of Ophthalmology]], restarted the diploma courses for post-graduates, inaugurated the Orthoptic School and re-instituted the [[Oxford Ophthalmological Congress]]. In her own words, she had 'cleared the Augean stable' in nine months.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 127\u201328</ref>\n\nHer efforts were recognised by the university in 1945 when she was given a personal professorship: the first woman to receive one at Oxford. She was Titular Professor there from January 1945 until 30 September 1947. Mann was also a Fellow of [[St Hugh's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/oxford-people/women-at-oxford|title=Women at Oxford|accessdate=1 February 2019|work=University of Oxford}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nMann became acquainted with [[William Ewart Gye]], known as Bill Gye, who was Director of the Imperial Cancer Research Fund at Mill Hill, and his wife, [[Elsa Gye|Elsa]], during the war. After Elsa death from cancer, Mann and Gye married in December 1944.<ref>{{cite journal|title=W. E. Gye. M.D., F.R.C.P., F.R.S,|journal=British Medical Journal|date=25 October 1952|volume=2|issue=4790|pages=945\u2013946|pmc=2021835|pmid=12978397}}</ref> Mann became stepmother to her husband's three sons from his first marriage. She did not change her name on marriage, as the complications arising from having two Professor Gyes in the same household were easily foreseen.\n\n==Australia==\nMann had first visited Australia in 1939 as the British Medical Association's representative at the 1st Annual General Meeting of the Ophthalmological Society of Australia (B.M.A.). She flew there in an Imperial Airways Flying Boat, which took a week to fly at low altitude from Southampton to Melbourne. She gave a number of papers and made the return journey \"with the feeling that the gloom of Europe would soon descend, and that this brilliant, sunny and friendly land would be blotted from my memory\" (Mann: ''The Chase'').<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 108\u201311</ref> In 1949 she and her husband set off for Perth and Melbourne on an autumn cruise.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 138</ref>\n\nThe introduction of the [[National Health Service]] in Britain had drastically changed Mann's work and she was dissatisfied with the impact on ophthalmology. Perhaps more pressingly her husband had retired from Mill Hill and was suffering from ill-health which was exacerbated by the English winters. They were immediately smitten with Perth. Mann purchased a bungalow in Dalkeith, resigned from Moorfields, and arranged for all their belongings to be shipped to Australia.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 140\u201341</ref> Here they conducted experiments on cancer viruses using in-bred strains of mice to ensure consistency.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), pp. 141\u201342</ref> She started a private practice as an ophthalmologist, which was always her insurance against economic uncertainty.<ref name=Chase-143>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986), p. 143</ref>\n\n==Trachoma research==\nBill died in 1952, leaving her bereft, 'I was unhinged; so tired that I was almost insane'.<ref name=Chase-143/> She regained her balance by working and traveling. Shortly after his death she took an assignment reporting on the incidence of eye disease for the Western Australia Public Health Department. This assignment extended to four years and provided incontrovertible proof of endemic trachoma among the indigenous population.<ref>Ida Mann, ''The Chase'' (Fremantle, 1986)<!-- page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nShe traveled extensively throughout Australia and Oceania studying the incidence of eye disease in different races and cultures, with particular reference to the Aboriginal people. This research produced the classic work, ''Culture, Race, Climate and Eye Disease'' (1966).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/blue-plaques/ida-mann/|title=Mann, Dame Ida (1893-1983)|accessdate=1 February 2019|work=english-heritage.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nMann published extensively in the area of eye anatomy and eye disease, publishing many scientific articles and several books. She also wrote on her travels and findings relating to [[trachoma]], published under her married name '''Ida Gye''' or a pseudonym, '''Caroline Gye'''. These were ''China 13'' and ''The Cockney and the Crocodile''.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Honors==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\n*She was appointed CBE in 1950 and DBE in 1980 for services to the welfare of Aboriginal people. \n*She was inducted into the Ophthalmology Hall of Fame in 2007. \n*She received an honorary Doctor of Science from Murdoch University (Perth, Western Australia) in 1983.\n\n==Death==\nDame Ida Mann died at her home in Perth in 1983, aged 90.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Publications==\n* Ida Mann, ''The Development of the Human Eye'' (Cambridge, 1928)\n* Ida Mann, ''Developmental Abnormalities of the Eye'' (Cambridge, 1937)\n* Ida Mann and Antoinette Pirie, ''The Science of Seeing'' (Harmondsworth, 1946)\n* Ida Mann, ''Culture, Race, Climate and Eye Disease'' (Illinois, 1966)\n* Caroline Gye, ''The Cockney and the Crocodile'' (London, 1962)\n* Caroline Gye, ''China 13'' (London, 1964)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Mann, Ida, ''The Chase: an autobiography'', edited by Ros Golding (Fremantle Arts Centre Press, 1986)\n* Radi, Heather (editor), ''200 Australian Women'', Women's Press: Sydney, 1988.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070620185928/http://www.oxfordeyeupdates.com/page/page/2123438.htm Profile], oxfordeyeupdates.com; accessed 1 April 2014\n*[http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/IMP0041b.htm Profile], womenaustralia.info; accessed 1 April 2014 \n*[http://www.snof.org/maladies/embryohist.html Profile], snof.org; accessed 1 April 2014\n*[http://www.bodley.ox.ac.uk/dept/scwmss/wmss/online/modern/mann-ida/mann-ida.html Catalogue of papers of Ida Mann held at the Bodleian Library], University of Oxford website; accessed 1 April 2014\n*[http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0690b.htm Mann, Ida Caroline (1893\u20131983)] in ''The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mann, Ida}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Australia]]\n[[Category:British humanitarians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British writers]]\n[[Category:Australian Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:People from West Hampstead]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Surgeons]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Medicine for Women]]\n[[Category:Women ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:Vision scientists]]\n[[Category:Female vision scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Ernest Lane", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ida_Mann"}
